@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
============================================================================
@{b}From The Editor's Desk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

Hello and welcome to the December 2025 issue of WhatIFF?, it is hard to 
belive that we are soon ending 2025. It seems that each year passes more
swiftly than the last. So much has happened this year with regards to world
events and the Amiga, as such I am happy to say we have a suitably packed 
issue for the last one of the year.

Firstly, thank you to everyone who contributed to this issue and over the 
year, the magazine would not be exist without your hard work. 
                                                                      
This issue has been put out in record time of two months instead of the 
usual four months so it is more surprising that we were able to get as much
content as we did. For interviews we have five this issue from Edwin van den
Oosterkamp the creator of BassMX, Zooperdan, Aiden Holmes creator of the 
PCMCIACD driver, Electric Black Sheep and Alinea Amiga Shop. Reviews of the
PicoWyfy, BassMX and retrospective review of the Blizzard MKIV. We have lots
of guides and articles from our regular writers and someone even sent us in
a letter!

With 2025 coming to close we have much to look forward to, TheA1200 launch,
more stock of the A6000, AmigaOS 3.3 and the continuing drama of the 
Commodore aquisition, already while writing this I can see new drama 
unfolding online with legal cases being brought against other companies with
the Commodore name.

Thank you to everyone who has been downloading and reading the magazine, it
always gives me a boost to hear from you and I make sure to forward your 
comments onto the regular contributors.

Finally I have to apologise for the music playlist this issue, due to a lack
of contributors I had to make all the music myself. Hopefully next issue we
can get some decent and professional sounding music again.

For those of you who read this section, thank you and I wish you a most 
Merry Xmas and a happy new year. See you on the flip side!

@endnode

@node talkback "Letters From WhatIFF? Readers"
@toc contents
============================================================================
@{b}Talk Back: Reader Letters@{ub}
============================================================================
Welcome to Talk Back, the section of the magazine where we publish a select
few of the letters that we receive. Thank you to everyone who has written in
and those who have gone on to write articles for the magazine. We always
welcome any written contributions to the magazine. Everyone has a unique
perspective and Amiga story to tell. If you wish to write to the magazine
or contribute then please contact us at: @{b}submissions@whatiff.info@{ub}
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Hello Timo,

You ask for our Amiga Storys in the new WhatIFF Amiga Mag. so i just feel to
share my Amiga Story. Written on an A1200 (hope it works) with YAM and
gmail.

When i was a Kid about 7-8 Years my Dad got on Xmas an C64 with Datatape
(without any Games). He was at a friend and saw some Games on the C64 and
was so happy about that. My Mother buy him a C64 for Xmas but for me it was
the first time to see a Computer. Before i only saw some Computers at Movies
etc. so over the xmas days we had only the C64 Manual with some Basic
Programms of a flying Ballon with a C logo. No Games at All but it was so
crazy to write something and get a result on screen. It was Magic, later i
buy Games on Tape and play on the C64 of my Dad. He did nothing with it
really, maybe playing a Game sometimes.

I got a real freak and buy later a Disc Drive and copy floppys with friends,
like Teenager do. Then we got slowly Informations about the next C64 (Amiga)
and it was crazy to believe what it should do compared to our C64.

So i got one of the early 1.3 Amiga500 for my Bday, and there was a
tankmouse inside. I never use a mouse before ? but it look funny. I build it
up and call some friends if they got any Amiga Games, then they just came
with Maniac Mansion and Shuffelpuck Cafe. Mansion i know already from C64
and i was total impressed with the high graphics on the Amiga. Shuffelpuck
was a mouse game and it was difficult to use a mouse. At end i was happy, so
i did learn to use a Computer mouse. I still play this Game sometimes just
for the Nostalgic feeling.

Later i upgrade a secound drive for less disc changes, an memory expansion
for Games that need it. Hell it was a great time, we feel part of something
big coming. We feel like pioneers of Computers, speak our language about
RAM, ROM, Chips and meet people at Conventions. Mostly i had the Problem
like you, i was very Young at that time so people did not tread me serious
at begin.

CHAPTER II

Later people switch to PC as Commodore was going under like Magazines show
PC Games and the CDROM was coming forward. So like my friends i switch and
the Begin till Pentium3 times we had much fun, lan Partys and playing Quake,
Unreal Tournament all this games.Starcraft, WarcraftII and even Shadow
Warrior had a Multiplayer.

2023 i was at a point that no PC Game brings me joy anymore, PC Games got
into Survival/Building Games to Farm hours of real Time to build something
like a House. It feel more like Work after Work ! Guilds demand you to be
online on specific Times to Raid something. I did not feel happy anymore !

So my Gamer PC got OLD and i had to choose to upgrade the PC for NextGen RTX
or do something complete other... So i decide to buy myself the A1200 that i
never had but always wish for and switch from PC back to Amiga for 700Euros.
Yes i read in your mag about "Amiga get out of reach" but i just had to buy
it and a New PC Gaming Rig would be more.

Maybe this is a strange Story becouse most people want to read about the
"past" and not the "now" but Amiga is Still active and People are coming
back.

So i install everything with more Luck as Brain :) Workbench 3.1 wow never
saw that and how many things changed. Then AmigaOS 3.2 came out right in
time for me. The learing curve was not so high, i remember startup-sequence
and other things back from the days. Also there was much new Software out
between 1995-2024 things i never hear of, or could use of demands. Like
Amiga Writer a tool i use many times, Photogenics a HD Paint/Photo Programm
(i just remember Deluxe Paint), Apdf Amiga can read PDF ? wow great. Wonders
over Wonders what all happend in the Time i was on PC. So many modern
Programms like Internet Protocol and iBrowser, YAM, FTP Programms and even
Videoplayers for Mp4.

I think this time it was even better as in the Past, i wonder so much about
the modern Amiga 68k ! Doom, Duke3D, Descent so many Games and still Games
coming like SettlersII or small indie Productions from Users. I think the
best Amiga Time i have right now in 2025. No Joke! i got a PiStorm on my
A1200 and everything flows like butter. It feels like a modern PC but on
Amiga such experiance i had never before and it makes me smile everyday new.

I know PiStorm is not liked by every Amiga User but to upgrade now to a PPC
Turbocard, RAM, PCMCIA Network, HDMI Out, RTG is JUST NOT PAYABLE at last
here in Germany. So the PiStorm is a easy and cheap way to get on that Level
without paying a Mercedes for Upgrades.

I search on ibrowser for Mod Pages and Download Music, New Mod Music and
play them in Hippo while doing stuff. Like i scan over Wlan on my Brother
and can upload it directly on my Router Drive (256GB USB Stick) my Amiga can
access the FTP of the Router and i can Download my Scans, then i open them
in Photogenics and resize them smaller for better work performance. Crazy or
? i can upload documents to the Router and Print them over Mobile Phone,
there should be a way to script automatic Printing but i'm to noob for this.
It hears compilcated but when you do it 20-30 times, it just is a matter of
1 minute.

Just wanted to say everything works and for the rest i own my Mobile Phone
like Youtube. I rencode mkv to divx and can watch movies on my Amiga over
FroggerNG. Mp3 over AmigaAmp. Well what else do you need ? WHDLoad brings
joy of classics and 68060 Games are running smooth on the PiStorm.

So under the line, i would say i'm a very happy Person now ! More happy as
with PCs or Classic Amiga, i love the amiga workflow or just listen to a Mod
on my Amiga while reading a Comic in PDF format. It relax me, it make me
feel nostalgic warm and doing something on Computer is FUN Again.

PS: Im German so excuse my English, i just learn School English but hopefull
you will understand the meaning even without correct typo.

Kind regards

Mike Swat

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode


@node shelltalk "Where Amigans Speak Freely!"
@toc contents
============================================================================
@{b}Shell Talk@ - PiStorm Ponderings@{ub} - by: @{"ByteBandit" link bytebandit}
============================================================================

It's funny how the Amiga scene moves in cycles. One minute we're all arguing
about the purity of ECS versus AGA, or whether WHDLoad counts as "real" disk
usage, and the next minute we're bolting Raspberry Pis onto our motherboards
like some sort of cybernetic Franken-Amiga. Yes, I'm talking about the 
mighty (and sometimes *too* mighty) PiStorm.

Don't get me wrong: the PiStorm family is an incredible technical 
achievement. The fact that a tiny ARM board can mimic a 68030, 040, or 060 
faster than anything Commodore ever dreamed of is mind-bending. The 
PiStorm32 Lite for the A1200 pushes things even further, letting people jump 
into RTG modes, crank up absurd resolutions, and even run old PC software 
through emulation layers that make your faithful 68k blush. It's *amazing*. 
But it's also¦ well¦ a little bit weird.

Somewhere along the line, the original soul of the machine starts to slip
through our fingers. When an A1200 is suddenly running Windows 3.1 apps at
warp speed, displaying 1080p desktops, and pretending to be a retro PC, you
start to wonder whether you're still using an Amiga or just a Pi with a very
large and nostalgic dongle hanging off it.

And then there's the cost. For the price of a PiStorm setupâ€”Pi, SD card, 
power, adapter, riser boards, cooling, and all the bits and bobs you *swear* 
you won't need until you do, you could run UAE on a PC, a laptop, or even a 
standalone Pi with far fewer headaches. They'll run the same software, often 
faster, and in some cases with better compatibility. So the argument 
becomes: if what you want is raw speed and convenience, why not just go full 
emulator and spare your vintage hardware the stress?

The thing is, the Amiga has always been about the *experience*. The whirr of
the drive. The feel of the keyboard. The odd little quirks that only real
hardware gives you. The PiStorm, in all its brilliance, risks flattening that
experience into something more generic, something powerful, yes, but also 
less distinctly Amiga.

Of course, some users love it. And fair play to them! It's their machine, 
their desk, their retro future. But as more and more videos pop up of people 
running old PC software on their PiStorm-boosted A1200s, using RTG to reach 
resolutions that would make a Picasso IV weep, it starts feeling like the 
line has blurred a bit too far. When your Amiga spends more time pretending 
to be a 486 than it does running Deluxe Paint, you might want to ask 
yourself whether you're augmenting the machine¦ or replacing it.

Maybe I'm old-fashioned. Maybe I like my Amigas like I like my coffee: warm,
slightly unpredictable, and definitely not pretending to be a PC. But as the
PiStorm revolution races ahead, I find myself hoping we don't lose sight of 
why we kept these machines alive in the first place.

Power is fun. Speed is fun. Running Doom at 200 FPS on an A500 is hilarious.
But the heart of the Amiga was never about raw horsepower. It was about the
unique mix of charm, design, and creativity that no other machine had.

So enjoy your PiStorms, just don't forget to let your Amiga be an Amiga 
once in a while.

-- ByteBandit

@endnode

