@node miraripreview "Hardware prereview: Mirari"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
@{b}Hardware preview:Mirari PPC Board@{ub} - by @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
============================================================================

New Mirari PPC motherboard for AmigaOS4 and MorphOS !

@{b}So, what is Mirari PPC?@{ub}

It's a soon to be released PowerPC motherboard being produced by a small 
team of Dutch Amiga fans who also happen to be hardware engineers.They 
named the new PPC motherboard Mirari which translated from Portuguese 
means miracle (based on a small team delivering new PPC hardware in the 
Amiga verse nowadays is truly a miracle!)

@{b}What are the specs of this new board?@{ub}

Form Factor: micro-ATX compatible
Dimensions: 244 x 170 mm (L x W)

CPU: QorlQ T1042 multi-core processor (up to 1.6 GHz)

Memory: DDR3L SODIMM, 1.35V

    Type: DDR3L SODIMM
    Voltage: 1.35V
    Speed: Up to DDR1600
     
Expansion Slots:

PCIe x16-4 lanes occupied (PCIe 2.0)
PCIe x4-1 lane occupied (T10x2 PCIe 2.0)
PCIe x1-1 lane occupied (PCIe 2.0)

Storage Interfaces:

SATA: 2x SATA 2.0 (T10x2 only, 300 Mbit/s)
NVMe: 2x NVMe slots (one slot mutually exclusive with SATA)

Additional Features:

USB Ports: USB 3.2 Gen1
FPGA: Onboard FPGA for additional functionality
Operating System Support: Compatible with various PPC Linux distributions, 
AmigaOS 4, and MorphOS

@{b}What's the release date?@{ub}

According to news from AmiWest in the US and Amiga40 in Germany all hardware 
prototypes are completed. Linux and MorphOS are running fine and the 
AmigaOS4 team is working on the kernel and drivers. The estimate release 
date is mid 2026.

@{b}How much will it cost?@{ub}

Between 500-600 euros

@{b}Why should you buy this?@{ub}

1. You loved your Phase 5 PPC back in the day and you still love Amiga :-)

2. You're old PegasosII, micro AmigaONE, or AmigaONE G3-SE or XE can't be 
fixed anymore or you want a quicker system and also use a modern video card.

2. It's half the price of currently available PPC hardware from A-Eon 
(AmigaONE X5000) and also approx. 300 euros cheaper than the SAM460ex from 
ACube Systems.

3. Overall speed wise it's approximately 75% of the AmigaONE X5000/20 
system.

@{b}Still interested?@{ub}

Follow the Mirari Team at @{"https://mirari.vitasys.nl/" system "openurl https://mirari.vitasys.nl/"}

Wishing all Amiga fans world wide a Merry Christmas/Happy Holidays 2025!!!
G. Scolieri
@endnode

@node blizzardreview "Hardware review: A look back (and forward!) at the Blizzard 1230-IV Turbo"
@toc reviews
============================================================================= 
@{b}Hardware review: Blizzard 1230-IV Turbo@{ub} - by @{"Martyn Bampton" link martynbampton}
============================================================================= 

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Blizzard 1230-IV Turbo Board
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Phase 5 Digital Products (later DCE)
@{b}Available From@{ub}
* AmiBay
* eBay
* Other second hand markets
@{b}Price@{ub}
It varies but depending on condition and configuration expect to pay 
anywhere from about 250 to 700 be it pounds, dollars or euros!
@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
* An Amiga 1200.
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
* Amiga 1200

@{b}A look back (and forward!) at the Blizzard 1230-IV Turbo@{ub}

                @{"Blizzard Card & Manual" link Images/blizzard1230_1_big.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/blizzard1230_1_small.iff"}
@{b}Introduction@{ub}

In the late 90s I was lucky enough to get a few Phase 5 boards.  I spent a
lot of time reading various magazine reviews, adverts and going over the
specifications and performance figures, this was going to be amazing and I
couldn't wait!  They weren't cheap and it took a lot of summer job income to
afford them but I was always impressed with their quality and just how much
of an upgrade such boards provided.  One of those boards was the highly
recommended Blizzard 1230-IV for the Amiga 1200, the fourth and final 030
board. In later years Phase 5 sold the rights to DCE who continued to
manufacture and sell the board, in some cases with a different RTC battery.

The Blizzard mounted a PGA 68030, PGA 68882, a 72 pin SIMM socket and a real
time clock on an A1200 trapdoor accelerator card - a common configuration
but the Blizzard also had an edge connector for an optional SCSI card as 
well as a refined design.  There were various configuration options from a 
plain 030 board with an empty SIMM and FPU sockets to 030 CPU + 68882 FPU + 
SCSI Module and up to 256 MB RAM in two SIMMs - one on the board and one on 
the SCSI card - It takes a 70 ns or faster module up to 128 MB in size per 
socket.
                @{"Blizzard Front" link Images/blizzard1230_2_big.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/blizzard1230_2_small.iff"}
I won't go into too much detail on the SCSI card but if you're interested
here's an excellent article by Steven (Lyonsden Blog):

@{"https://lyonsden.net/blizzard-scsi-kit-mkiv" system "openurl https://lyonsden.net/blizzard-scsi-kit-mkiv"}

@{b}Hardware and Installation@{ub}

My Blizzard came with a 50MHz 68030, 50MHz 68882 FPU and an empty SIMM 
socket. I bought a 16 MB SIMM from a local computer shop - If you didn't buy 
the card with a 68882 or SCSI module you could always add them later but you 
should always add RAM.  There are two jumpers on the board, one for RAM 
timings (for a 10% speed increase if using RAM faster than 70 ns) and one 
jumper for enabling the built in MapROM function.  Everything else is set 
automatically.

There is also a rechargeable lithium coin cell battery soldered to the board
for keeping the real time clock going.  Mine didn't leak (they don't tend 
to), it could even still hold a charge!  Jan Beta has a video detailing how 
to replace the battery should you need to:

@{"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-sdXLAXbpfQ" system "openurl https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-sdXLAXbpfQ"}

The board arrived in an appropriately sized black corrugated cardboard box
with a nice black cardboard sleeve bearing the Blizzard logo and 
specifications.  Inside the box the board is wrapped in an antistatic bag
and cushioned with foam padding, there's also a 12 page instruction manual
in German and English.  There's no software included as configuration is
handled by autoconfig and jumpers, though you should probably make sure you
have the 68030 and MMU libraries.  I vividly recall that Installation was 
both exciting and rather nerve wracking, after carefully upending my A1200 
and removing the trapdoor cover I took the Blizzard out of the antistatic 
bag and laid it on top (of the bag) and added the SIMM in preparation. You 
don't have to open your A1200's case but looking back it might make it 
easier if you do.

After placing the card in the A1200 and lining it up (there's not a lot of
space, it's a tight fit) I recall pushing it firmly and nothing happening.  
Do I have it the right away around?  What other way could it possibly go?  
After some self doubt, nervous wiggling and more pushing it finally slid 
home!  I put the trapdoor cover back on and plugged everything back in. 
You'd think after over 25 years and lots of computer building I'd be less 
apprehensive about doing it now but it's still a little challenging.

@{b}Software and Performance@{ub}

The manual states that the board provides a "400% to 500% performance 
increase" and "significantly accelerated graphics".  I eagerly powered the 
A1200 and it booted fine thankfully, quicker too and with a whopping 16MB 
Fast RAM showing in Workbench!  The first thing I did was...  SysInfo!  
Then AIBB for the beach ball test, I remember being absolutely thrilled at 
the results. It works!

Results will vary from computer to computer but expect MIPS scores in 
the high 9.x range and Dhrystones over 9000.  After benchmarking I put it 
through its paces with VistaPro, Real 3D/Imagine/Cinema 4D, DPaint/PPaint
ImageFX, Brilliance, Wordworth - It's odd how you remember these things but 
it was such a cool experience, like having a brand new Amiga!  I used the 
computer for games and productivity fairly equally so of course I 
appreciated the performance boost in more demanding games.  I used to play 
Gunship 2000 and Wing Commander quite a lot and the Blizzard really helped 
there. When Alien Breed 3D 2 was released it even came with a promotion for 
a Blizzard 1230-IV (or 1260) in the game box!  Apparently "Blood flies 
faster in a Blizzard"! This was the card to have, well, until the 1240/1260
/PPC boards came out anyway.
                @{"Alien Breed 3D 2 Promotion" link Images/blizzard1230_3_big.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/blizzard1230_3_small.iff"}

@{b}Summary@{ub}

That Blizzard served me well, never gave me any trouble or overheated.  In
later years it and my A1200 ended up in a Micronik Infintiv tower case 
and ran Linux in addition to Workbench.  Well I really had no desire to 
switch to Windows!  Recently I rehoused the A1200 back in its original case 
as the tower had yellowed horribly in places and was always rather flimsy. 
Thankfully the computer booted first time, the Blizzard was still functional 
and aside from some slight label peeling it looks brand new!  I've decided 
to use that A1200 as it was in my bedroom growing up - complete with the 
Blizzard. Hopefully it will continue to provide the same performance boost 
for a quite while longer after 20 years in storage!  

I'm very glad I kept hold of it and my other Phase 5 boards, they've shot 
up in price recently and you're lucky to get one for less than the price of 
an A1200, never mind the SCSI kit.  If you happen to find a good deal or 
come across one hiding in an A1200 then absolutely grab it, you won't be 
disappointed.  However, the reality is a modern accelerator like the TF1232 
or even the TF1260 with a full 060 may be a more cost effective choice - 
you might not get a real time clock but you'll get 128 MB of RAM, FPU and 
an IDE interface.

@{b}Note on finding a 68030 or a 68882@{ub}

Unfortunately it's getting harder to find a legitimate 50 MHz 030 or 68882
FPU.  Most of what's for sale seems to be reconditioned used components that
ended up as electronic waste for "recycling" i.e. cleaned/relabelled.  
Perhaps resellers think customers want shiny chips that look new, rather 
than accurately marked chips that let us know what they're actually rated 
for.  So expect that many of the 50 MHz units are quite possibly relabelled 
chips which may have originally been any frequency up to 50 MHz - although 
later mask revisions typically tolerate this.

I'm going to do an article on this problem after my experience trying to 
find an original 50 MHz 68882 but in the meantime here are some resources 
for mask/date verification:

68030: 
@{"https://eharmon.net/retro/macintosh/motorola-processors" system "openurl https://eharmon.net/retro/macintosh/motorola-processors"}
68882: 
@{"https://68kmla.org/bb/index.php?threads/sourcing-legit-mc68882-fpus-data.46717" system "openurl https://68kmla.org/bb/index.php?threads/sourcing-legit-mc68882-fpus-data.46717"}

@{b}Pros and Cons@{ub}
+ Excellent build quality.
+ Great expansion options including SCSI.
+ Probably the best original 68030 accelerator for the A1200.
+ Up to 128/256 MB Fast RAM!
+ Built in MapROM function and memory access speed option.
+ Speed!
- Expensive, more capable newly built options are available for around the
  same price.
- A bit of a tight fit.

@{b}Other Key Points:@{ub}
* Many continue to function well even after 3 decades but you take your 
  chances.
* RTC clock battery probably needs replacing.
* Finding legitimate 50 MHz 68030 CPUs and 68882 FPUs can be difficult and a
  little expensive.
* Later boards manufactured by DCE may have non-rechargeable RTC batteries.

