@node picowyfyreview "Hardware review: Picowyfy"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:Picowyfy@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
PicoWyfy
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Niklas
@{b}Available From@{ub}
A314-cp Discord server via direct message
@{b}Price@{ub}
39 EUR
@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
Clockport
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
A1200 PiStorm
A1200 TF1260

@{b}Review@{ub}

About two years ago I reviewed the A314-cp for WhatIFF? and gave it a very
favourable review. In my opinion it was the most convenient and easiest way 
to get your Amiga connected, at the time. The developer of the A314-cp 
Niklas Ekstrom released a new project, the PicoWyfy last year. It is a 
wireless network interface controller (WNIC) that uses the Raspberry Pi
Pico W and connects to the Amigas clock port, like the A314-cp.

So, how does it differ from the A314-cp? To begin with it might be a good 
idea to revisit the A314-cp and what it does. When I had covered the A314-cp 
I focused on its ability to provide WIFI access without too much hassle. 
However, it is not only a WIFI adapter, you can use it as a file server, MP3 
decoder and access the Pi's command line interface. In this regard the 
A314-cp allowed you to use the faster CPU of the Pi for some Amiga tasks.
 
While not in the same vein as the PiStorm it still allows more than pure 
WIFI access.

The PicoWyfy in this regard, is a different kind of beast.  It is a more 
refined product with a focus on providing easy and fast WIFI access in any 
Amiga with a clockport.

After having enjoyed the A314-cp I was interested to see how the PicoWyfy 
compares. At the moment it is only possible to purchase it via the A314 
Discord channel by contacting Niklas. He was quick to reply and very 
helpful to any questions I had. Payment was by PayPal and he provided fast
shipping with tracking.
                @{"PicoWyfy Image 1" link Images/PicoWyfy_2big.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/PicoWyfy_2small.iff"}
It took about a week for the parcel to arrive and came packed in a padded
envelope. So, if you order becareful to check your mail box as it is easy
to miss it, like I did. While the enevlope was smaal, the PicoWyfy is tiny! 
The A314-cp is not a big card by any means but the PicoWyfy takes it 
further. 

When I first got my A313-cp, I had some troubles setting it up and connected
to my router. It involved editing files on the Raspberry side and then 
copying the necessary files and using a static IP address. While it is easy 
with hindsight, for one who has not done any networking on the Amiga it can 
be a steep and frustrating learning curve. I am happy to say this time  
Niklas has made it as painless as possible. 
                @{"PicoWyfy Image 2" link Images/PicoWyfy_3big.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/PicoWyfy_3small.iff"}

                @{"PicoWyfy Image Installed" link Images/PicoWyfyIn_1big.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/PicoWyfyIn_1small.iff"}
@{b}Installation@{ub}

To begin with I made a fresh install of Roadshow and deleted any files 
related to my previous installs of A314-cp and Wifipi. I then copied over
the files from the Picowyfy archive that can be found here:
@{"https://github.com/niklasekstrom/picowyfy" system "openurl https://github.com/niklasekstrom/picowyfy"} contained in the archive are four 
files:

        @{b}File name@{ub}             @{b}Location for files@{ub}
	---------------------+--------------------------
	* picowyfy.device    |	DEVS:Networks
	* PicoWyfyCtl	     |	C:
	* picowyfy.config    |	DEVS:
	* PicoWyfy	     |	DEVS:NetInterfaces	

Once you have the files installed you can set up the TCP/IP stack, and I 
recommend using Roadshow for this. It is still the best way to get your 
Amiga online due to still having support and the added benefit of speed.

Where as with the A314-cp it was recommended to use a static IP address the
PicoWyfy works best with DHCP, and this is very easy to setup with Roadshow.
All you need is to set up the access point for the PicoWyfy. This is 
accomplished with PicoWyfyCtl programme, which should be kept in the C:
directory. You can use the following commands:

	* status	prints status of the network adapter
	* scan		scans for wifi networks in range					
	* connect       connects to your chosen network
	* disconnect    disconnects from the current network

It is incredibly easy to set up, for example if your router's name is 
'AmigaX' and the password '1234', all you need to type is:

	PicoWyfyCtl connect AmigaX 1234

It will connect right away, with no hassles or issues. At the moment it is 
not possible to save a favourite network, however it is simple enough to add 
the above line to your startup sequence. 

	C:PicoWyfyCtl connect AmigaX 1234 QUIET

QUIET was added as I did not have it pop up a Shell screen informing you of
connection.

If you use a clock port expander the PicoWyfy can still be used as long as
you enter the correct port address in the 'picowyfy.config' file in Devs.

@{b}Overall Impressions@{ub}

Getting your Amiga online in the past involved many steps and configurations
with the advent of the A314-cp and Wifipi the entire process has been 
greatly simplefied. The PicoWyfy has made it even easier taking out many of
the steps that were necessary before. Now all you need to do is install
Roadshow, copy the files to the proper locations, enter your router details
and away you go.

Before getting the PicoWyfy I was using a PiStorm and tried Wifipi but ran 
into numerous issues. It was a pleasant surprise when the PicoWyfy arrived
and I was online in under 5 minutes. If a dunce like me can get online with
out issues then this card is fool proof.

So, it is easy to install but what about the speed? I achieved download 
speeds of 579kB/s and upload speeds of 383kB/s. This was done with the 
AmiSpeedTest.

So overal not too shabby. 

It may not be as speedy as the Wifipi but the PicoWyfy works with ease where 
as the Wifipi is known to have issues connecting to certain routers. There 
have been other users who have reported speeds of 1MB/s but this was when 
copying a file over a local network. Saying that, the card provides enough
download bandwidth for downloading files from Aminet, using YAM or surfing 
the web in IBrowse.

One thing I should mention though is that the card can cause the Amiga to 
freeze under certain circumstances. I found this to be most common if 
playing a game from Workbench. It seems that it is an effect of the card 
is connected to an access point and waiting for packets. The freezes are
random and can even occur when running AmigaTestKit, this happens when
running memory tests. However, if you shutdown the PicoWyfy the freezes
disappear and you can run your games or AmigaTestKit without issue. If you
are using Roadshow it can be accomplished by typing the following into the
Shell:

	ConfigureNetInterface PicoWyfy offline

With this command all my freezing issues disappeared, once your are finished
gaming and are back in Workbench, you can reboot or type in the same command
but instead of 'offline', use 'online'.

	ConfigureNetInterface PicoWyfy online

I must thank the people on the A314-cp channel for helping me with this as I
was under the impression my Amiga had failing Chip ram.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

Finally we have a network interface that is easy to setup and works like you
hope would. Niklas has created a top product that deserves much recognition
for being as close to a plug in and play solution for net connectivity you 
will get on classic Amigas. Combined with Roadshow this is in my humble
opinion the best way to get online, no other solution comes close to the ease
and stability as the PicoWyfy.
to create.

*A Few Words from Niklas Elkstrom*

Finally please have a look at his github to find out about other projects 
Niklas is working: @{"https://github.com/niklasekstrom" system "openurl https://github.com/niklasekstrom"}

During a chat on Discord I asked him about the maximum potential speed of 
the PicoWyfy when writing this article, he had this to say:

"I think it should be higher than for A314-cp. I saw this tweet where a guy 
saw speeds over 1.1 MB/s for picowyfy: 
https://x.com/AmigaWorld/status/1764250418731692320

But I guess it depends a lot on which Amiga it runs in. I haven't seen 
anywhere near those speeds on my Amiga. I get around 3 Mbit/s download 
speed.

Another thing I would say is that I think A314 and PicoWyfy are very 
different things. PicoWyfy a wireless network interface, that's it, while 
A314 gives many different services, shared file system, the pi terminal 
integration.

To me, the actual speed numbers don't matter that much. As long as it is 
convenient to copy files from aminet (for example) then that's enough for 
me. The convenience of having an internal wifi network interface is more 
important than having the fastest possible connection (for me, YMMV of 
course)."

@endnode

@node bassmxreview "Hardware review: BassMX"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:BassMX@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
BassMX
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Edwin van den Oosterkamp
@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"www.ebay.co.uk/itm/236187306353" system "openurl https://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/236187306353"}
@{b}Price@{ub}
Approx. 20 GBP
@{b}Hardware Requirements@{ub}
None
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
A1200/TF1260/PicoWyfy/OS3.2.3

@{b}Review@{ub}

BassMX is a board created by Edwin van den Oosterkamp, well-known for his Amiga
books *Classic Amiga OS Programming - An Introduction* and *Bare Metal Amiga
Programming*.

The Amiga's audio has always inspired mixed opinions. In 1985 Paula's sound
capabilities were groundbreaking, but by the late 80s and early 90s users
began to feel the limitations: hard-panned stereo and only four audio channels.
Yet with time, Paula has gone from being criticised to being celebrated. Its
constraints now feel more like character, something that pushes creativity
instead of restricting it.

Still, there's one issue almost everyone agrees on: the Amiga's extreme stereo
separation. The usual workaround is using a single audio cable for a mono
output, but this sacrifices the stereo field entirely.

Over the years I've tried all kinds of solutions: standalone amps, mixers, audio
boosters, and sometimes just embracing the mono output. They all worked in
their own way, but none felt quite right. Then, during one of my routine Amiga
patrols, I discovered the BassMX.

What makes the BassMX interesting is that it doesn't simply merge both channels
into mono. Instead, it filters the bass from each channel and mixes it into the
opposite side. This keeps the stereo image intact while providing a more
balanced, fuller sound. If you want to dive deeper into the technical side, you
can read the interview with Edwin van den Oosterkamp @{ "here." link edwinoosterkampinterview }

If you're interested in buying one, you can find it on eBay or order directly
from Edwin. I contacted him directly because eBay wasn't shipping to Japan at
the time. The total cost was just over 26 GBP including postage. Edwin shipped
it promptly with tracking, and a little over a week later a small parcel arrived
with the BassMX logo on top.

                @{ "BassMX Image 1" link Images/BassMX_1big.iff/MAIN }
                @{IMG "Images/BassMX_1small.iff"}

                @{ "BassMX Image 2" link Images/BassMX_2big.iff/MAIN }
                @{IMG "Images/BassMX_2small.iff"}

The board itself comes as an open PCB with rubber feet to keep it from sliding
around. Each end features a pair of RCA sockets, and one side includes a
mini-USB port for power. A USB-to-mini-USB cable is included. Labels clearly
mark the input and output, but there's no LED or indicator to show when the
device is powered. It's a compact board, and I found it fits neatly on the
vented section of my A1200, staying put thanks to the rubber feet.

                @{ "BassMX Image 3" link Images/BassMX_3big.iff/MAIN }
                @{IMG "Images/BassMX_3small.iff"}

@{b}Sound is everything@{ub}

So, how does it actually sound? My setup uses inexpensive Funology speakers,
which, despite their size, offer a warm tone and surprisingly punchy bass. With
the BassMX connected, the improvement was immediate. Because it spreads bass
across both channels rather than collapsing everything into mono, the sound
becomes noticeably fuller while still keeping a genuine stereo image.

Even with my modest speakers, the Amiga's audio gained presence, warmth, and a
more coherent low end. Some users may prefer the simplicity of true mono,
easily achieved with a Y-adapter, but in doing so they would miss the nuance and
character the BassMX preserves. I honestly didn't realise what my setup was
missing until I heard the BassMX in action.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

If you want to retain the original character of the Amiga's audio while giving
it a more balanced, modern feel, the BassMX is a brilliant little upgrade. It's
affordable, simple to set up, and offers a genuine improvement to the overall
listening experience. Highly recommended for anyone who cares about getting the
best sound from their Amiga.

@endnode

