@node wordzreview
@toc gamereviews
============================================================================
@{b}Game Review: Wordz@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================
@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Wordz
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Zooperdan
@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"https://zooperdan.itch.io/wordz" system "openurl https://zooperdan.itch.io/wordz"}
@{b}Price@{ub}
Name your own price
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Amiga 500 Kickstart 1.3
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/TF1260/PicoWyfy/OS3.2.3

@{b}Review@{ub}

I confess to being a bit of a book worm, each time I travel to work I have
two books in my bag along with a newspaper. Looking down at my smartphone
watching videos or scrolling through endless boring content is not my idea
of fun. But word searches are fun, at least for boring old me, and I enjoy
taking my time in the newspaper to the crossword puzzles. After I had
reviewed YEET in the last issue Zooperdan came out with another game, Wordz
which we could not fit into the October issue.

So, what is Wordz? As you can already guess by the intro and game title it
is a word search game. Usually I world not include a review of such a game
but this one has been dragging me back to Amiga, again and again. The game
is available from Zooperdan's itch.io page and is a name your own price 
game.

The game is small, simple and efficient. When you load up the game, you are
presented with a simple but effective title screen and no music. There is
an option to enter a code to jump stages. Starting from the first stage you
have a list of words on the left and a grid of letters on the right.

I confess being confussed for a while when searching for words, I was looking
and could not find anything. But, then I found out what I was doing wrong. In
the typical word search you have words going down, and left to right or 
diagonal. Wordz throws this out the window, requiring you to go left, up, 
right, down, down, left, and up. Essentially throw out the window what you 
think you know of traditional word searches and then the game starts to make
sense. When I realised I should not being thinking of Wordz as a traditional
word search game it became much easier to find words and turned into a very
enjoyable game. As far I know there was no background music but then again
I made this mistake with YEEP, I blame the years of going to raves and DJing
which gave me hearing loss. Dan kindly pointed out in an email exchange about
the music albeit it at a low volume. Maybe we need an ex-ravers music mode
for those of us with hearing loss. Sorry for that rather odd aside, back to
the game. Anyway, I decided to turn up the volume until I could hear the 
buzzing static of the Amiga audio, so yep, this time no BGM audio.

There are some nice audio touches such as sound effects when you find a word
and then move onto the next stage. I appreciate this as when I read I rather
not listen to music, I know for some it helps them read but for me I prefer
the quiet or rather constant whistling in my ears.

Letter selection is done via the mouse and left clicking and holding while
you drag out the selection of letters. That is all that is needed, the game
is entirely mouse controlled.

And that is pretty much it, it can be frustrating at first if you think of
the game as a typical word search but once you understand the game play
mechanics it becomes a great game to play. I even use this for my students
and they enjoy it a lot. Funnily enough  they figured out how to play the
game much faster than I did, I guess they are not so set in their ways yet.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

A fun little game that taxes your brain and hopefully teaches you some new
vocabulary along the way. It is a good idea to have a dictionary with you
as you might want to look up some of the words. Another little gem from
Zooperdan. Also please checkout our @{"interview" link zooperdaninterview} with him in this issue.

@Endnode

@node blokreview
@toc gamereviews
============================================================================
@{b}Game Review: BLOK@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================
@{b}Product Name@{ub}
BLOK
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Zooperdan
@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"https://zooperdan.itch.io/blok" system "openurl https://zooperdan.itch.io/blok"}
@{b}Price@{ub}
Name your own price
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
1Mb Chip Ram (A500+, A600, A1200)
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/TF1260/PicoWyfy/OS3.2.3

@{b}Review@{ub}

Originally I was not planning to review this game in the December issue as 
we already have a review of Wordz but after playing this game I had to 
include it in this issue. BLOK came out in early November of this year
and is a puzzle game where you roll a blue block through 24 levels of
increasing difficulty.

The game is available from Zooperdan's Itch.io page and is a small download
of around 400Kb, I downloaded it on my Mac and it was easy to email it to
my Amiga.

The game can be started from Workbench, and when you first start the game
you are presented with a title screen with the following options: New Game,
Enter Code, View Credits, How to Play, Quit Game. The screen has a nicely
done 3D render of the block and gameplay area.

Selecting New Game will take you to the first stage, everything is 
presented in isometric 3D. You can control your block by the arrow keys or 
a joystick.

The Enter key is used to select an option, during the game if you press the
Enter key it will bring options to continue, reset and quit the back to the
main menu, where you can go back to Workbench.

I was very surprised when I first started to play the game as the block
is unlike anything  I have seen on the Amiga before. In BLOK Dan has 
rendered the block animation in 3D and then taken those frames to make a 
very modern looking game that would not look out of place on a smart phone.

Once I got over the amazement of the block animation the game took over and 
in typical Zooperdan style this game is easy to pick up but hard to master.
Rolling the block becomes natural in no time and the first few stages are 
easy to figure out. But that is short lived as the levels quickly get 
harder. Initially figuring out the correct orientation of the block is
required but after a few levels you come across other obstacles such as
buttons, timers, crumbing floors, bridges and grating which you should not
stand on. Finally there are the lava sections which you can only roll over
once. 

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

Once again Zooperdan has created a fun and unique game, it amazing with YEET
onlu just recently released and he comes out with BLOK. And despite that this
is an incredibly fun game, the graphics are very nicely done and I still 
admire the 3D block animation after having played several times. The gameplay
is simple but addictive, perfect for a puzzle game. Once again you deserve it
to yourself to download BLOK and remember to donate to Dan for all his hard 
work, even just a few pounds goes a long way.

@{b}Pros and Cons:@{ub}
+ Brilliant block animation
+ Fun and addictive
+ Great music

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 10/10
Graphics: 10/10
Sound:    8/10
Overall:  9.3/10

@Endnode

@node chaoticcrazycastlereview
@toc gamereviews
============================================================================
@{b}Game Review: Chaotic Crazy Castle@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================
@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Chaotic Crazy Castle
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Alberto Sgaggero
@{b}Available From@{ub}
@{"https://fourseasons.itch.io/chaotic-crazy-castle-for-commodore-amiga-500" system "openurl https://fourseasons.itch.io/chaotic-crazy-castle-for-commodore-amiga-500"}
@{b}Price@{ub}
Name your own price
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
A500 KS1.3/512KB
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/TF1260/PicoWyfy/OS3.2.3

@{b}Review@{ub}

Chaotic Crazy Castle is a game that was programmed in just two weeks on an
A500 in AMOS. The developer Alberto Sgaggero says this shows, but does it?

Find out below.

The premise of the game is that you play a rather short mage who is on a
quest to obtain herbs that he can use in a potion to make himself taller.
Game play is spread over the several castle rooms and involve jumping onto 
ledges, avoiding enemies and collecting herbs. There is no way to kill
and enemy so you need to plan your movements ahead of time and learn the
patterns like true oldschool games. Movement is by the joystick or keyboard
with the fire button/space bar used for jumping.

On first loading the game you are presented with a Winners Don't Take Drugs
inspired screen from the days of arcades. This version has a boing ball in
the middle with the FBI replaced with the Retro Bureau of Nostalgia.
Beneath it you have the ever famous "Begone drugs, you shall not pass!"
by Ghandalf the White. Press the space bar or fire button and you are taken
the main title screen that looks very reminicent of the Castlevania title
screens. The graphics look good and come with BGM. Before starting the
game you have several options:

	* Start
	* Music on/off
	* Sound on/off
	* Lives 5
	* Fast  off/on

You can set lives up to a maximum of 9 and unlimited after that, fast on
will speed up the gameplay. I found it difficult to go back to the standard
speed after playing Fast mode.

There are various tiles around the levels that will be required to access 
certain herbs or rooms and they are as follows:

*Wood tile* 		
You can jump through it from the bottom to top, but not vice versa.
*Stone tile* 	
You can walk over it, but you can´t jump through it from below.
*Stair tile* 		
Like an escalator, when your is over this tile, you will automatically be 
taken up.
*R/L green warp tiles*
They will automatically push you forward, you cannot walk back, unless you 
jump.
*Down green warp tile*
This will automatically take you down.
*Centered green warp tile*
These tiles will slow down your left-right movements.
*Spring tile*
As you would expect, this gives you more height when jumping.
*Exclamation tile*
Instant death!

By default you start the game with 5 lives and 0 of 33 items/herbs to be 
collected. The only actions you have are moving left to right and jumping
if you jump on an enemy you die, so you need to be careful and time all
your jumps perfectly to clear the enemies and then run. Each of the enemies
have a set pattern so it pays to bide your time and memorise the pattern
as it is very easy to die in the game. If you die you are dropped back into
the game play area and this is where the game has some issues. On one stage
I died and was stuck in a loop where my character would fall at the same 
time as a passing enemy causing me to die again and again until I quit and
restart the game. This happened several times and it is possible to get out
of some of those situations by pressing left or right to alter your fall but
if you are falling directly on an enemy it is too easy to get stuck in a 
death loop like I did. Saying that, I am not that good of a gamer and it 
could just be that I am really bad at this game and others will not have the
same issue.

Aside from that small niggle the game is a lot of fun, the graphics are cute
and colourful. They remind me of some of the PC Engine games I used to play.
The various enemies while deadly are also charming, and lok very similar to 
classic Japanese console games. Each of the enemies have small animations 
which is a welcome touch. In fact there is a fun tribute to Monty Python
when you lose your final life and a giant foot comes down from the sky to
crush you.

You get some nice music while you play and sound effects, overall it is a 
very well presented game.

It can be a tough game if you are used to simply jumping on the heads of
enemies, but once you understand how to play the game it becomes very 
enjoyable. Moving between the rooms and figuring out where they connect to
get to otherwise inaccesible areas is great fun. It is not a fast game but
one that you need to think ahead to not get stuck in the future. I should
mention that there is no save feature but due to the size of the game this
should not be an issue. 

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

Chaotic Crazy Castle is fun, challenging and cute game that has a great
presentation and will keep you coming back for more. I am very much looking
forward to the second game if Alberto makes one as this game is a lot fun
and made me want more. The lovely graphics and small things like the Monty
Python tribute make it the perfect game to play this winter season. 

@{b}Pros and Cons:@{ub}
+ Tough but fun game
+ Good graphics and sound
+ Reminds me of games on the PC Engine
- I wish it could be longer
- Can be frustrating when getting into a death loop

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 7.5/10
Graphics: 8/10
Sound:    7.5/10
Overall:  7.6/10

@Endnode



