@node keepingamigaalive "Keep the Amiga alive"
@toc articles
=============================================================================
@{b}Keep the Amiga alive@{ub} - by: @{"Roald Strauss" link roaldstrauss}
=============================================================================

Imagine having the power to keep the Amiga alive forever. Or at least for 
the rest of your life. For as long as you can enjoy it. Imagine having that 
power for any other platform as well. And any other creative field you can 
think of. In fact; anything in life you treasure. Imagine being able to keep 
all of those things alive.

Now brace yourself for an epiphany: That's not a fantasy at all! You @{b}do@{ub} 
have the power to keep the Amiga alive! And many other things as well!

But it's highly probable that no one ever told you how to use that power of 
yours. So I'm going to tell you now.

Let's start by listing a few examples of things we would like to be able to 
keep doing:

- Watch new cool Amiga demos
- Play new Amiga games
- Listen to new Amiga Protracker or OctaMED music
- Read articles in new issues of WhatIFF? Magazine
- Buy new Amiga hardware

All of those examples have one main thing in common: They're all products 
made by someone. Sometimes a single person. Other times a group of people. 
The reason cool Amiga demos exists, is because someone made them. Same with 
all the other examples.

So let's say you've discovered a composer that makes MODs you really enjoy 
listening to. Or a writer who writes articles you really enjoy reading. Or 
a game-developer who makes games that really entertain you. How do you then 
use this awesome power or yours to make sure these people will continue 
making all these things for you?

It's ridiculously simple. I'll tell you know:

@{b}You simply tell the authors that their work is awesome and appreciated.@{ub}

That's how simple it is: You make all of these creative people stay 
passionate, by telling them their work is awesome and appreciated. So 
whenever you stumble across something that adds value to your life, you 
should reach out to the authors and let them know how much you appreciate 
their efforts. Don't be shy. It's as simple as writing an e-mail.

Of course, if you @{b}really@{ub} wanna make an impact, then you go ahead and buy 
whatever creation the authors have made. Buy their games! (Even if it's not 
your favourite genre - just buy it to keep the developer interested in the 
platform).

If you @{b}don't@{ub} send your positive feedback, to let them know about 
your sincere appreciation, there's a big chance they will eventually stop 
creating more awesome demos / games / music / articles etc in the future - 
all because you didn't think about utilising your awesome power.

You see, there's another power that everyone has, that they sadly use 
@{b}all the time@{ub} for some reason: We're experts in @{b}complaining@{ub} about 
everything that doesn't go the way we want. Even before watching / playing / 
listening / reading etc, a lot of people are ridiculously quick to dismiss 
something - and post negatively about it on a random forum.

This means, that when you @{b}don't@{ub} post your @{b}positive@{ub} feedback with 
your sincere appreciation, then the majority of the feedback the creator(s) 
are getting, is negative. Because complainers are always quick to post. 
Self-entitled people complaining about every little thing that wasn't made 
the way they want it. Oh yes, the world is full of them.

And that means it's all up to you! Go forth into the world now, and utilise 
your awesome powers to keep all good things alive. We depend upon you!
@endnode

@node bytebanditarticle "Looking Back at 2025: The Amiga Moves Forward"
@toc articles
============================================================================
@{b}Looking Back at 2025: The Amiga Moves Forward@{ub} - by: @{"ByteBandit" link bytebandit}
============================================================================

2025 proved that the Amiga is not just a memory piece, but a living
platform. New hardware, game releases, brand revivals, and community
movements show the spirit still thrives. From indie platformers to
officially licensed classics and even fresh life for the Commodore
name this has been one of the most eventful years in recent memory.

@{b}40th Anniversary@{ub}

2025 marked forty years since the first public unveiling of the Amiga 1000
in 1985. Exhibitions across the world highlighted early models including
the A1000, A500, and A1200. Classic machines were brought out of
storage, fans revisited old demos and games; a tribute to how radical
the Amiga once was in terms of graphics, sound, and multitasking.

Though decades have passed, the enthusiasm surrounding these celebrations
showed that the Amiga remains a machine with a beating heart.

@{b}New Hardware in 2025@{ub}

Two major hardware stories drew attention this year.

== THEA1200 / Full-Size A1200 Replica ==
A full-sized A1200 recreation often referred to as THEA1200 was
shown at Gamescom 2025, offering a working keyboard and aiming to bring
back classic A1200-style Amiga into a modern *retro-futurist-form*.
This move resonates for those who seek the classic form factor but with
some modern convenience.

Pre-orders opened in November with a planned shipping window of mid-2026.

== FPGA Based Next Gen: Apollo A6000 ==
Meanwhile, the FPGA powered Apollo Computing pushed forward with the debut
of the Apollo A6000, a modern Amiga-compatible machine built around the
AC68080 core, combining classic 68K compatibility with updated hardware
(HDMI, modern RAM, storage, etc.).

For many in the community, the A6000 stands as proof that Amiga can
evolve and not just be preserved.

@{b}New Games & Software@{ub}

2025 saw a surprisingly healthy flow of new and revived games for the
Amiga.

- **The Settlers II: Gold Edition** after nearly 30 years since the
  original release, a fully licensed, optimized Amiga port of the iconic
  RTS arrived on October 18, 2025. The release offered three editions:
  Digital, Box, and a limited Collector's Edition: giving both casual
  players and collectors something to enjoy.

- Homebrew & indie scene remained vibrant: titles like **Phantom Leap**
  by HooGames2017, and **Master of Minefields** from Digital Worlds Studio
  surfaced this year. Such releases show that for those willing to
  tinker and code, the Amiga remains a platform for creative expression not 
  just nostalgia.

- On the software side, AmigaOS 3.2.3 launched in 2025, bringing over
  50 fixes and improvements, and enhancing compatibility - including
  support for modern accelerator setups like PiStorm-style expansions.
  These updates prove that classic 68K Amigas can still stay relevant even 
  in 2025.

@{b}Commodore Revival@{ub}

One of the most headline-grabbing stories of 2025 was the revival of
the brand behind the Amiga's origin: the Commodore name. In mid-2025 a
fan-led consortium officially acquired all 47 original Commodore
trademarks, forming a new entity to steer the brand onward.

While that acquisition doesn't automatically give them control over AmigaOS
or existing IP like ROMs, which remain under different stewardship, it opens 
the door to a broader *retro-futurist* vision.

The revived Commodore already reissued an FPGA-based recreation of the
classic 8-bit home computer (the Ultimate C64), and signaled interest
in expanding into broader retro-computing hardware, a move that has
reignited hope among some Amiga fans that future hardware or licensed
products might emerge under the Commodore banner.

@{b}Community & Obituaries@{ub}

2025 was not without its shadows. The Amiga/Commodore community lost a
longtime veteran:

- **Gail Wellington** (b. 1940 d. 2025), known as a former Commodore-UK
  staffer and influential in software/product support for the Amiga
  (and related platforms), passed away earlier this year. She was once
  described as mother of CDTV, and her contributions to the Commodore
  software side helped shape the user experience for many during the
  platform's early days.

Her death was met with sorrow across retro-computing circles, reminding
us that many of the pioneers who made the Amiga possible are now aging
but their legacy endures in the hardware, software, and community
spirit still alive today.

@{b}Closing Thoughts@{ub}

Looking back at 2025, the Amiga stands at an unexpected crossroads. On
one hand, retro-accurate recreations and new indie games offer nostalgia
and preservation. On the other, FPGA-powered next-gen hardware, OS
updates, and a revived Commodore brand suggest potential for growth and
reinvention.

For veterans, 2025 is a warm reminder: the glow of the Workbench screen
is still bright. For newcomers, it's an invitation: whether you pick up
a boxed game, dust off an old A1200, or join the next wave of Amiga-
inspired projects, there is an Amiga waiting for you.

*ByteBandit tip:* Honor the old but be ready for something new. The
Amiga spirit lives in what we build next, not only in what we preserved.

@endnode

@node sceneornot "To be or not to be a scener"
@toc articles
============================================================================
@{b}To be or not to be a scener@{ub} - by: @{"Roald Strauss" link roaldstrauss}
=============================================================================

To be or not to be a scener. Is that the question?

I still remember discovering The Scene in the early 90s, and the
feeling of finally having found the group of people I belonged with:
The ones that were just as geeky and passionate and weird about
computer creativity as I was. I'd been scouting for people like that
for a long time. Someone I could better relate to. Someone I could
share my hobby with. Someone I could spar with, exchange
tips'n'tricks with, so that we could both learn more about our shared
interest. Such like-minded people had previously seemed impossible for
me to find anywhere. They were definitely non-existent in primary
school.

But primary school never managed to impress me in any other aspect
either. I remember often wondering what the point was with school. The
teachers mostly seemed tired of both their job and the pupils, and I
never saw the logic in why we needed to learn most of what was
taught. But I suspect most of us felt that way back then.
The highlight of my day was to come home from school, switch on my
Amstrad CPC464 and play around with BASIC programming. I felt I
learned @{b}much@{ub} more about coding and math and even physics, at home
in front of my Amstrad CPC, than I did in school - even though we
actually did have classes in school that were supposed to teach us
about computers and programming.

@{i}All we did in computer classes at school, was to input the data of
all the pupils of the school into a database system the teacher had
written (no GDPR whatsoever back then), presumably because he thought
it was his ticket out of teaching. He needed his database system to be
full of data in order to be able to give a proper demonstration to a
group of important men in fancy suits. But apparently he didn't manage
to impress these men, because he kept teaching.@{ui}

Going to bed at night was the low-point of the day, because it meant
that the next activity on my "Incredibly boring things I'm forced to
do" list, when I woke up, was to go to school and waste all day there.

School was this place we were forced to go spend most of the day on
incredibly boring things we never ever had any use for later in life.
Like for example read the most boring books in the world - and then
prove that we had actually read it - or be scolded in front of the
whole class if we hadn't. I'm sure some day in the future, humanity
will look back at that era and cringe in shame of how primitive our
ways once were.

As a result, my desire to read was completely destroyed. To this day I
still haven't read a single novel since primary school, and reading in
general is something I try to avoid. I simply lost all interest in
reading, with the exception of minor academic texts, when searching
for answers about whatever technical topic I'm currently exploring.
Like for example noise reduction in 8-bit audio, or the specification
for various filetypes like MOD, or how to detect a frequency in a
sample. Stuff like that.

And it probably seems a bit ironic that I don't like reading,
considering how much I actually like to @{b}write@{ub}. Especially when
looking at the size of my @{"8-bit Memoirs" system "openurl
https://www.8bitmemoirs.com"} project, as well as the articles and
tutorials I've written for WhatIFF? Magazine so far. But no one ever
@{b}forced@{ub} me to write texts like those. That's the key. That's
how you stay passionate about something. By not being forced to do it.
All good things in life can be completely ruined by being forced to do
them.

@{b}Discovering The Scene@{ub}
When I grew older and (finally) replaced my Amstrad CPC464 with an
Amiga 600, my creative hobby doing BASIC programming was replaced with
Protracker MOD tracking. Most of my spare time was now spent making
music in Protracker. Coming home from school to my Amiga (where I was
actually learning stuff), was still the highlight of the day. I used
my music as an outlet that let me express the things I experienced in
life. I had a theory that most artists did this. And this theory was
confirmed when I began listening to MODs created by other musicians.

This was back in the day before The Internet was a common thing. The
only place I had access to The Internet, was on the Windows PC's at
school. So when I learned that my Amiga could read 720 kB PC formatted
disks, I began bringing a bunch of such disks with me to school every
day, in order to download files from Aminet and bring new interesting
software and other files with me home. I bet a lot of us did exactly
that in those days.
The school had its own little shop where students could buy
accessories like pencils, pads, calculators - and floppy disks! And I
soon became their biggest customer of floppy disks.

Bringing 10-20 disks full of Aminet content with me home every day soon
became the biggest incentive for attending school. On days where I felt
more like staying at home, it was the thought of exploring new Aminet
content that made me go anyway. The new highlight of the day was to
come home from school and check out the downloads of the day: Listen
to MODs made by other artists, watch demos and check out a few games.

It was while listening to MODs by other artists, that I realised I was
part of this global group of artists somehow. The ones who created
music simply because it was their passion - not to make money, but
simply because being creative was a fundamental part of who they were.
And for a long time, MODs became my primary source of music. Mainstream
radio didn't interest me at all, and neither did professional albums on
CD. No other music had the soul and authenticity that MODs had. MODs
were created by the @{i}real@{ui} artists, I felt. This was where the
@{b}real@{ub} quality was, created by artists I could relate with.

It was around this time I learned that there was a name for this group
of artists. This group was called "The Scene". And I remember it made
me instantly feel even @{b}more@{ub} connected to everyone. A large
group of fellow artists located all over the world. Everyone one being
creative on different computers in various fields, making their art
freely available for everyone. Artists sharing and enjoying each
other's music and graphics and coding art. It felt very altruistic to
me that everyone simply gave away their art to the world, and all they
wanted in return was to enjoy everyone else's art. So refreshing to
finally see some altruistic behaviour in this otherwise exceedingly
selfish world. There was no doubt: I definitely belonged in this group
of people.

In December 1994 me and my Amiga mates then went to The Party in
Denmark. It was here I was introduced to diskmags, when Buzz Diskmag
#5 was released. For some weird reason, I had never seen a diskmag
before. And it was a rather positive surprise for me to discover that
The Scene @{b}also@{ub} consisted of @{b}writers@{ub}.
Experiencing Buzz Diskmag #5 made me feel even @{b}more@{ub} connected
to The Scene. @{b}And for the first time in many years, I found myself
enjoying reading non-academic texts again.@{ub} That really says it
all, doesn't it? @{b}Primary school literally ruined my desire to read,
and Buzz Diskmag #5 brought it back again.@{ub}

Not to a degree that I ever started reading novels again though. I
still don't do that. There's just something very icky about a paper
book. A black Times New Roman font on a dry white background... ew...
But diskmags were something entirely different. A bright ambient
coloured font on a dark background, while cosy background music is
playing, and with little pieces of drawn art embedded in the texts.
Everything created by various artists in The Scene.

To this day I still love the concept of diskmags, and would love to
see more of them. There's just something incredibly cosy and relaxing
about a diskmag, that a website will never have.

For this reason, I spent years encouraging my fellow Amstrad CPC geeks
to create a new diskmag for the Amstrad CPC, until I finally gave up
and decided to created my 8-bit Memoirs eBook project as a
diskmag-looking creation instead.

@{b}"Demosceners compete"@{ub}
For many years I walked around with the impression that I was "a
scener", and I felt a strong coherence with all other sceners.

But then came a day where I realised something about The Scene that
made me question if I'd ever actually truly belonged. And to this day
I still have those doubts, leaning mostly towards "probably not
really".

To find out for sure, let's first be sure we have the correct
definition of what a scener is. In these modern times, when you google
for something, it's difficult to avoid getting an AI answer back.

@{i}A demoscener is a member of the demoscene, a digital subculture that
focuses on the creative use of computers to produce non-interactive
audiovisual presentations called "demos". These demos showcase creative
coding, computer graphics, and electronic music, often pushing the
limits of what's possible on a particular platform. Demosceners compete
in "compos" (competitions) at demo parties, where they share and
celebrate their art.@{ui}

And that corresponds pretty much exactly to my own perception of what a
demoscener is. But it doesn't clarify whether I'm a scener or not.

I'm definitely on board with the first part: Focuses on the creative
use of computers to produce (in my case) MOD music.
I also put all of my music online, making it free to download and
listen to for everyone.

My tracks are @{b}not@{ub} free to @{b}use@{ub} without my permission
though. For example; a game-developer isn't allowed to put my music in
his game without my permission. And I also don't upload my tracks to
any of the scene related sites (anymore). I only publish my tracks on
my own site: IndieGameMusic.com - where I'm offering freeware and
commercial licenses to game-developers for using my tracks in their
games. I'm not sure how scener'ish that is, but let's get back to
that.

I'm also on board with the "often pushing the limits of what's
possible on a particular platform" part. For me, it has always been a
fun challenge to (try to) make "MODs that doesn't sound like MODs", by
creating a sound with a quality that isn't typically heard in a MOD.
The best kind of feedback I can get is when people actually doubt that
it is in fact a MOD they're listening to.

I enjoy finding various techniques to try out. For example; ways to
reduce quantisation noise and alias noise, avoid click'n'pops,
optimise harmonic distortions, finding interesting ways to create new
sounds and various effects as well as finding interesting ways to
create smooth loops, and have the MOD use only 3 channels and 80 kb
while sounding like much more.
So far so good.

But then the definition continues with "Demosceners compete", and
that's where I'm definitely out. I don't create my music to compete
with anyone. I generally don't compete with anyone in anything. I only
ever participated in about two one-hour compo's I think, and that
wasn't really to compete, but rather because I was bored and curious
to see what such a one-hour compo was like. Frankly, I have never
liked any kind of competition in any kind of category in any aspect of
life. I don't even feel you @{b}can@{ub} compete in art. And I do very
much feel that any kind of creativity anyone is doing in The Scene, is
exactly that: Art.

So I guess it just comes down to this question: Is it a mandatory
thing to participate in the competitions, in order to be considered a
scener? Or is it an optional thing? I'm not sure.

Obviously it won't be difficult to find people in The Scene who will
say that the competitions are entirely optional. But if we take a look
at the actual activities going on in The Scene, aren't the
competitions always the main focus then? Seems to me they are. And
it's also difficult to simply exist in The Scene without being asked
why I don't participate in the competitions. So it seems to me that
the general mentality is indeed focused on the competitions.

This also became apparent to me when checking out other diskmags up
through the years, trying to find the same cosy atmosphere that I
found in Buzz Diskmag #5 back in 1994. I felt most of the newer
diskmags focused more and more on the competitive side of The Scene,
and I found myself struggling to find the cosy atmosphere in that.
I preferred all other kinds of texts: Articles where the only
scenerish thing about them was that they were written by another
scener. Random stories and/or deep philosophical thoughts and
observations from fellow sceners. Somewhat like this article here
you're reading right now.

But this category of texts seemed to vanish from diskmags in general
up through the years, and I therefor lost the interest in actual
diskmags again. But I never lost the enthusiasm for my own vision of
how such a diskmag should be. To this day I'd still like to see a
diskmag like that; where most of the content is simply sceners sharing
stories and thoughts and observations and experiences about whatever
various topics. "Sceners exploring / experiencing the world".
But I realise I'm probably the only one in the world who'd enjoy a
diskmag of that calibre.

I have to admit that the feeling of coherence with The Scene has kept
fading over the years. It's almost impossible for me to find the cosy
atmosphere I remember from the good old days, despite my efforts of
trying to bring it back, by creating my MODs and writing articles like
this one. This of course could very well also just be because I'm
getting older. Because with age comes the unavoidable realisation that
the world is a rather messed up and depressing place. And this state
of sad epiphany obviously makes it difficult to experience everything
with the same joy as we did when we were younger. But that's exactly
why I seek these cosy moments being creative with my music and my
writing. Hasn't our creativity always been our escape from this insane
world? (Or was that just me?)

I know that composing MODs has always been @{b}my@{ub} escape from the
hectic daily stressful demands. And I still do enjoy MOD composing, on
the rare occasion I succeed in making something I'm satisfied with.
And my primary goal with my music is to give other people that same
cosy feeling that other artists gave me up through the years. A
feeling of coherence, belonging, relaxation and positive vibes. A
temporary escape of their own, and/or inspiration for their own art.
That's what I've always felt The Scene was about: Giving each other
positive inspiration and entertainment in exchange for positive
inspiration and entertainment. Boost the creativity for fellow
sceners.

That's my goal when making music, when writing articles like this,
when I created IndieGameMusic.com, whenever I put my music on
IndieGameMusic.com, when I occasionally create a little retro game for
a classic platform, when I (try to) collaborate with developers on any
platform doing music experiments to learn what can and can't be done
on that particular platform - to forward this knowledge to all other
sceners interested in that platform.

To me, that way of thinking is exactly what I thought The Scene was
all about. It's definitely what I would like The Scene to be all
about. Sceners helping fellow sceners be sceners.

But that perspective may very well just be my own illusion. Because
far too often I'm met with a rather opposite attitude, which reveals
that this perspective of mine is a rather rare one. The enthusiastic
scene spirit that I expected to be met with here and there, has been
difficult to find. Sometimes it actually feels like The Scene is dying
from some kind of cancer, caused by all the non scene-spirited people
who only joined The Scene much later than the rest of us, for the sole
reason that it was now suddenly considered cool to be a scener - and
they wanted in on it.

That of course happens in any kind of community, and it's always the
main cause of fragmentation. So maybe I'm simply on a new quest these
days: Find the fragment I belong in - if such a fragment exists
anymore.

Can anyone point me in the general direction of the fragment in The
Scene consisting mainly of philosophically enthusiastic creative
non-competitive artists, whose main goal is simply to inspire each
other and share tips'n'tricks etc?

The question still remains though:
To be or not to be a scener (in that fragment)... Is that the
question?
@endnode

@node amigainsight "Amiga Insight"
@toc articles
============================================================================
@{b}Amiga Insight: Amiga Shops@{ub} - by: @{"ByteBandit" link bytebandit}
============================================================================

There was a time when walking into a computer shop meant a glimpse into the 
future. Rows of beige boxes hummed under fluorescent lights, demo disks 
looped colourful graphics, and salespeople with pocket protectors promised 
the dawn of a new era. And for a few golden years in the mid-to-late 1980s, 
that era was ruled by one name: Amiga.

The Amiga didn't just arrive as another home computer; it burst onto the 
scene with a promise of multimedia before multimedia was a word. But how it 
reached users hands and which shops took the risk to sell it tells a 
fascinating story about two markets with very different sales cultures: 
the United States and the United Kingdom.

@{b}The American Dream Machine@{ub}

Commodore launched the Amiga 1000 in July 1985 at a glitzy New York event 
that felt more like a movie premiere than a computer launch. Andy Warhol 
was there, famously painting Debbie Harry's portrait on an Amiga screen. It 
was clear Commodore wanted the Amiga to be seen as something more than just 
another beige box of microchips.

In the United States, the strategy was deliberate: avoid the toy aisles that 
had swallowed the Commodore 64 and move into specialist computer retailers 
and upmarket department stores. Commodore wanted prestige.

Early on, the Amiga 1000 appeared in the same kinds of shops that carried 
Macintosh and IBM PCs. Stores like Software Etc., Electronics Boutique, and 
ComputerLand stocked them, while chains such as Montgomery Ward, Macy's, and 
VideoConcepts featured them on shiny glass counters alongside camcorders and 
VCRs. For a brief moment, the Amiga was the luxury computer you could buy 
next to a new colour TV.

Mail-order operations soon caught on too. One of the most important was 
Creative Computers (later known as PCM, Inc.), which began selling Amiga 
systems by mail in 1987. Their thick catalogues, filled with Amiga 
accessories, RAM expansions, and graphics boards, became a lifeline for 
users far from major cities. Even US Amiga magazines initially such as 
Amazing Computing Amiga and Amiga World had pages full of advertisements 
filled with Amiga goodies from the likes of Creative Computers.

But not everything was smooth sailing. Independent dealers often distrusted 
Commodore, still smarting from the company's aggressive pricing of the 
VIC-20 and C64, which had cut into their margins. Many retailers refused to 
carry the line at all. The result was an uneven network: strong pockets of 
Amiga fandom surrounded by vast PC territory.

As the 1990s rolled in, IBM compatibles flooded the market, and the Amiga's 
U.S. presence faded fast. By the time Commodore went bankrupt in 1994, most 
of its American retail allies had already turned to DOS and Windows. The 
Amiga, once sold under bright neon banners, was now found only through 
mail-order outfits and a handful of passionate resellers who refused to let 
the dream die.

@{b}The British Invasion@{ub}

Across the Atlantic, things looked very different. In the UK, the Amiga 
didn't just sell it exploded.

Where the U.S. had tried to pitch the machine as a high-end business 
computer, Commodore UK took a different tack: make it fun. The Amiga 500 
was sold in colourful bundles with names like The Batman Pack or 
The Cartoon Classics Pack, packed with games, paint programs, and a mouse 
that kids could actually use. That strategy made the Amiga a household 
name.

The face of that success was the Silica Shop, founded in 1982 in Sidcup, 
Kent. Originally a mail-order outfit, it grew into one of Britain's best-
known Amiga retailers, with storefronts and concessions inside major 
department stores. Silica's thick, glossy catalogues became as iconic to 
Amiga fans as the hardware itself. From joysticks and memory expansions to 
entire systems, if you needed it for your Amiga, Silica probably had it.

They weren't alone. Independent retailers popped up in nearly every city: 
Special Reserve, Micro Anvika, Power Computing, RCS Management, and 
countless small high-street computer stores. Even large chains like 
Dixons and John Lewis occasionally carried the Amiga line, especially 
during the A500's heyday.

What made the UK unique was the culture around it. Every month, magazines 
like Amiga Format, CU Amiga, and The One overflowed with full-page ads from 
these shops. Some had photos of shelves stacked floor to ceiling with boxed 
copies of Deluxe Paint to Lemmings. Others offered mail-order deals with 
free joysticks and posters. Buying Amiga gear was as much a community 
experience as it was a transaction.

While the U.S. struggled to convince office managers that the Amiga belonged 
on a desk, the UK had no such doubts. For British gamers, graphic artists, 
and budding musicians, the Amiga was the desk.

@{b}Decline and Legacy@{ub}

As the 1990s rolled on, PCs and consoles began to erode the Amiga's 
dominance. Even Commodore UK, one of the company's most profitable 
subsidiaries, couldn't survive the parent company's collapse in 1994. Silica 
Shop soldiered on for a couple more years before eventually closing in 1996, 
and many of its contemporaries followed suit.

Yet, the Amiga never truly disappeared. In the early 2000s, a new wave of 
online stores emerged, catering to the retro revival. Shops like AmigaKit 
(founded in 2004), Vesalia and Alinea (founded 2005) kept the platform alive 
with hardware repairs, accelerator cards, and even new cases and keycaps. In 
some ways, these are the spiritual successors to Silica Shop and Creative 
Computers the same passion, just updated for the internet age.

@{b}The Shopfront That Time Forgot@{ub}

The history of Amiga retail isn't just about who sold the machines it's 
about how they sold them. In the U.S., the Amiga was a daring premium 
product that struggled to find its market among cautious dealers. In the UK, 
it was a populist hit, sold with charm, colour, and character through a 
network of independent retailers who treated customers like club members.

Walk down any high street in the late 80s, and you could spot the glow of 
a 1084 monitor through a shop window. Step inside, and you might have found 
a kid transfixed by the latest Amiga game or if they were lucky a demo 
dreaming of making their own game one day. Those shops weren't just sales 
floors they were 
gateways into creativity.

Today, when you order an Amiga accelerator or new mouse adapter online, 
you're continuing a tradition that started in those noisy, neon-lit stores. 
The packaging might be smaller, the delivery digital, but the spirit of 
discovery remains the same.

@endnode

@node spouseandamiga "Living With a Spouse... and an Amiga"
@toc articles
============================================================================
@{b}Living With a Spouse... and an Amiga@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

The Amiga can be a challenging hobby. Repairs, new hardware, and upgrades 
can quickly make you feel as though your beloved machine is a black hole 
quietly devouring your savings. You *could* go the emulation route, it's 
free and convenient, but where's the magic in that? 

Many of us want to *feel* the Amiga: the clack of the keys, the whirr of the 
drives, the unmistakable sounds of our youth. That physicality simply 
doesn't translate through emulation.

As technology has improved and shrunk, physical media has all but vanished.
Videotapes, DVDs, Blu-rays, cassettes, CDs, and MiniDiscs have been replaced 
by MP3s and streaming. Homes have become tidier and more minimalistic 
because our media no longer needs shelves. Owning an Amiga today is, in many 
ways, a joyful rebellion against that minimalism; a return to cables, 
clutter, and tactile nostalgia.

This brings me to my predicament: I am an Amiga user, and my wife is a
minimalist. Recently, these two worlds collided.

Life in a Danchi
================

To set the scene, I live in Japan with my Japanese wife in a *danchi*, a 
type of public housing block built between the 1950s and 1970s. According to 
Wikipedia, "Danchi is the Japanese word for a large cluster of apartment 
buildings... Older danchi are sometimes compared to Khrushchyovkas." In 
other words: compact, practical, efficient and not exactly spacious.

Small spaces require minimalism. Over the years I parted with my 12" records
from my DJ days, my old consoles, and most of my DVDs and Blu-rays. What
remains: a few discs, a Super Famicom Mini, and my Amiga. Out of everything, 
the Amiga was the one item I couldn't let go.

So, with some trepidation, I agreed to let my wife convert the room where my
Amiga lived into a shared study. She is studying at university and never had 
a proper place to work. That room had been my online teaching and Amiga 
room.

                @{"Original Amiga Home" link Images/AmigaHomeBig_1.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/AmigaHomeSmall_1.iff"}

To my surprise, the flat now feels brighter and more open. It's actually 
lovely sitting together, the two of us working side by side. But that still 
left one important question: *Where does the Amiga go?*

Attempt 1: The Oshiire
======================

My first idea was to move the Amiga into the *oshiire* a large cupboard in 
the tatami room (*washitsu*) where futons are stored. It has a big shelf 
that fits a futon... or an Amiga setup.

                @{"Amiga Oshiire Home" link Images/AmigaHomeBig_2.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/AmigaHomeSmall_2.iff"}

It looked great, until I used it. Within minutes I was coughing from all the 
dust futons produce daily. My wife was equally unimpressed, so the oshiire 
was ruled out.

Before I continue, my wife insisted I include this quote: "Japanese women 
are like butterflies... but in reverse. Before marriage we are sweet and 
cute. After marriage *oni-wife*!" She demonstrated this transformation with 
an impressive oni-like expression. I'll let readers judge its accuracy.

Attempt 2: The Surprise Suggestion
==================================

With the oshiire ruled out, I slipped into *doshiyo* mode ("what do I do?").
Meanwhile, my wife calmly sorted the other closet and said, "Why not put the
Amiga on one of these shelves?"

Cue the instinctive Japanese "Ehh?", a sound I once swore I'd never make, 
but twenty years in Japan has worn down my resistance.

I inspected the shelf. Small, yes, but possibly...

I grabbed the monitor and A1200, slid them in, and against all expectations 
it fit perfectly!

                @{"Amiga Final Home" link Images/AmigaHomeBig_3.iff/MAIN}
                @{IMG "Images/AmigaHomeSmall_3.iff"}

It's tight, but with a low chair it's surprisingly usable. The mouse lives 
on a the table next to the closet, hardly a burden. My wife is happy, and 
thus so am I.

Cozy Computing
==============

And so, here I am, writing this article on my Amiga in a closet beside my 
wife while she studies. It's surprisingly cozy, and winter will likely make 
it even nicer. For anyone struggling with space or a spouse who prefers your 
retro gear out of sight, take heart. If I can enjoy my Amiga from a shelf 
in a closet, there is hope.

To be honest, I suspect my wife enjoys my new location even more. Whenever 
she asks, "Where are you?" and I reply, "I'm in the closet, I'm coming out 
now!" she can't help snickering.

As a teenager gaming in my bedroom, I never imagined this future. Living in
Japan brings culture shock, and living with someone from another culture 
adds another layer. But it also brings unexpected solutions, such as closet-
based Amiga setups.

From the new *WhatIFF?* Closet Headquarters, I wish you warm season's 
greetings and a wonderful start to the new year. Now, if you'll excuse me, 
I'm coming out of the closet to make tea for my wife and myself.

@endnode

@node a1200accelerators "Amiga A1200 Accelerator Guide"
@toc articles
============================================================================
@{b}Amiga A1200 Accelerator Reccomendations@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

This guide compares popular options for upgrading your Amiga A1200: PiStorm, 
ACA1234, and TF1260. Each has strengths depending on what you want from your 
Amiga: speed, compatibility, or flexibility.

The A1200´s 68020 CPU was fine in 1992, but many programs, games, and WHD
Load installs benefit from more RAM and faster processors. Accelerator cards 
unlock new performance levels, RTG graphics, and even network support.

@{b}Comparison Table@{ub}
Here is a side-by-side comparison of three accelerator cards:

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{b}Feature / Card@{ub}   | @{b}PiStorm (Emu68)@{ub}    | @{b}ACA1234@{ub}           | @{b}TF1260@{ub}
-----------------+--------------------+-------------------+-----------------
CPU Type         | Emu 68k (Pi)       | 68030@25-50 MHz   | 68060@50-100 MHz
Speed            | 200-800+ MHz eq.   | Mid-range         | High-end
RAM              | Pi RAM (hundreds)  | Up to 128 MB      | Up to 128 MB
RTG Graphics     | Yes (HDMI)         | No                | No
Networking       | Yes (via Pi)       | No                | No
Storage Options  | SD + IDE           | Onboard Fast IDE  | EIDE Connector
Compat. (Old)    | Very good          | Excellent         | Very good
Ease of Setup    | Medium             | Plug & play       | Plug & play
Price (approx)   | £80-£150           | £200-£250         | £300-£450
Availability     | Good               | Good              | Mixed
Extras           | HDMI, net, speed   | High compat.      | Extreme perf.
Best For         | Budget power       | Classic games     | Productivity
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}Setup and Installation@{ub}
Setting up each card varies. The @{b}PiStorm@{ub} uses a Raspberry Pi and software 
such as @{b}Emu68@{ub} or @{b}Musashi@{ub}, loaded via an SD card. It should
be noted that it appears @{b}Musashi@{ub} has not been updated in a while
with most preferring @{b}Emu68@{ub} which has frequent updates and also also 
gives better performance. 

Configuration takes some work, but once running, it delivers amazing speed 
and flexibility. While there has been a lot of work on getting the software
more compatible it still lacks the stability of the ACA and TF cards. Also
if you are stickler for small details there is a longer delay during power
on and rebooting than compared to a card with a real 68k CPU.

The @{b}ACA1234@{ub} is the simplest to install. You just plug it into the 
trapdoor slot, and it works immediately. It´s very compatible with older 
software and supports Fast RAM and map ROM features. The onboard IDE also 
gives a nice speed boost of up to 5.6MB/s plus a unique feature is the 
ability to boot from the A1200 PCMCIA slot.

The @{b}TF1260@{ub} uses a real Motorola 68060 CPU, often socketed by the user. 
It requires careful setup and sometimes cooling. When configured properly, 
it offers near 060 workstation-level power. You have several options 
available when purchasing, the most common and cheapest option is the LC060 
which does not contain an FPU. While this is the lowest cost option it does
tend to cause issues when running 060 targeted software as it often presumes
there is a complete 060 with FPU. In this regard buying one without a CPU 
and finding a cheaper rev. 1 or rev. 5 is a better option, you can find 
rev.1s for around £80-100 and rev.5s for £130-180.

@{b}Which One to Choose?@{ub}
If you mainly play games, you´ll want reliability and old-school compatibi-
lity - the @{b}ACA1234@{ub} is ideal. It´s fast enough for WHDLoad and almost 
every classic game.

If you like to experiment or use RTG graphics, the @{b}PiStorm@{ub} is incredibly 
flexible. It supports HDMI, file sharing with your PC, and network access. 
Performance scales with your Pi model.

For productivity, 3D rendering, or demos pushing the limits, the @{b}TF1260@{ub} is 
unmatched. The raw 68060 CPU power lets you run modern AmigaOS 3.2 setups 
smoothly, though heat and cost are factors.

@{b}Verdict@{ub}
In short:

- Go for the @{b}PiStorm@{ub} if you want fast, cheap, RTG, and network
  capability and don´t mind tinkering.

- Go for the @{bACA1234@{ub} if you want maximum classic gaming compatibility.

- Go for the @{b}TF1260@{ub} if you want extreme CPU performance for productivity
  and high-end Amiga use.

Each accelerator brings new life to the Amiga 1200. The right choice depends 
on whether you value flexibility, simplicity, or power.

@{b}Further Reading@{ub}
For more information and community help, visit:

- PiStorm Github @{"https://github.com/captain-amygdala/pistorm" system "openurl https://github.com/captain-amygdala/pistorm"}
- ACA1234 page   @{"https://icomp.de/shop-icomp/en/shop/product/aca1234.html" system "openurl https://icomp.de/shop-icomp/en/shop/product/aca1234.html"}
- TF1260 Forum   @{"https://www.exxoshost.co.uk/forum/viewforum.php?f=65" system "openurl https://www.exxoshost.co.uk/forum/viewforum.php?f=65"}

These resources include setup guides, firmware, and support forums.

@endnode

