@node aminetpulse "AminetPulse"
@toc contents
============================================================================
@{b}AminetPulse@{ub}
============================================================================

As 2025 moves into winter, the Amiga community remains active.
Here's a roundup of some of the more interesting packages uploaded to
Aminet recently: utilities, games, dev-tools and more. Worth a look
if you want to keep your classic or emulated Amiga fresh.

@{b}Utilities & System@{ub}
@node Sys 

- ShowMem 3.2 @{"http://aminet.net/package/util/moni/ShowMem" system "openurl https://aminet.net/package/util/moni/ShowMem"} 
  A graphical memory fragmentation visualiser, useful on classic Amigas to
  monitor free memory chunks and fragmentation. Dated Oct 2025.

- GoSnap 0.19 @{"http://aminet.net/package/util/cdity/GoSnap" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/util/cdity/GoSnap"} 
  Adds modern-style window snapping to Workbench windows (edges, corners),
  handy for RTG or multitasking Workbench setups. (Nov 29 2025)

- MuMin 47.10 @{"http://aminet.net/package/util/libs/MuMin" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/util/libs/MuMin"}
  MMU library archive for systems needing mmu.library support, useful for
  compatibility or systeml level tweaks on some setups.

- ADate @{"http://aminet.net/package/util/time/adate" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/util/time/adate"}
  A date/time utility for AmigaOS, offering flexible date parsing, epoch 
  conversion, and formatting. Good for scripting or timestamping needs.

- @{"openpci68k" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/driver/other/openpci68k"} 
  A PCI support package for 68k Amigas, helpful if you're using PCI 
  expansions or modern hardware interfacing (recent build 2025).

@{b}Games & Entertainment@{ub}
@node Games
 
- @{"OpenDUNE RTG 0.9.035" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/game/strat/OpenDUNE_RTG"}
  Open source port of the classic real-time strategy Dune II, rebuilt and
  optimised for modern Amiga RTG + 68060+ machines. A major modern Amiga
  strategy release (Nov 2025).

- @{"OpenDUNE AGA 0.9.034" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/game/strat/OpenDUNE_AGA"} 
  AGA compatible variant of OpenDUNE, for users on classic A1200 / A4000 
  with AGA graphics (no RTG needed). Great for keeping classic machines alive.

- @{"Connect4 AROS 1.0" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/game/think/Connect4_AROS"} 
  Simple but fun four in a row strategy/board game works on AROS / modern 
  Amiga like systems, ideal for quick gaming sessions.

- @{"Dodge These Balls" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/game/actio/dyb"}  
  Simple but fun dodge ball game by EntwicklerX, latest version now runs 
  safely on 060 machines.

- @{"SwitcherBoy" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/game/jump/SwitcherBoy_AGA_1.1"} 
  Final version of 1.1 of the new platform game, came in at 2nd place in the
  AmigaWave competition. For AGA Amigas with some fast ram, made in RedPill.

@{b}Development & Engines@{ub}
@node Dev 

- @{"Sevgi Engine 0.185" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/dev/c/Sevgi_Engine"}  
  A new open-source game engine for classic Amigas, offering templates, 
  based workflow, and support for graphics/sound, ideal for anyone looking
  to code games or demos on 68K hardware.

- @{"AMIGA_40th" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/dev/c/AMIGA_40th.zip"}
  A fun source anniversary package celebrating 40 years of Amiga; useful
  for experimentation, demo coding, or as a template for new projects.

- @{"SoftIEEE 2025" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/util/libs/SoftIEEE"}  
  Library providing IEEE floating-point emulation support, useful for
  software portability or cross-compiling older codebases.

- @{"Cross-Compile Toolkit" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/dev/cross/CrossCompileToolkit"}
  A recent toolchain update that supports compiling for AmigaOS from modern 
  Linux/Windows hosts helpful for developers working cross-platform.

- @{"Annotate" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/text/edit/Annotate_usr"}  
  A comprehensive text editor written for Amiga OS2.0, ported to OS4.0 and
  then ported back to AmigaOS3.0+. A modern text editor with lots of 
  features.

@{B}Other Notables@{ub}
@node Other 

- @{"AROS Live USB 2025" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/misc/os/AROSLive2025"}  
  A build of the open-source Amiga-like OS environment for modern hardware,
  bootable from USB and ideal for experimenting without vintage hardware.

- @{"Santastic" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/game/demo/Santastic"}  
  A festive game demo where you play Santa and trapese across various snowy
  landscapes to deliver presents to children around the world.

- @{"GoShell" LINK "https://aminet.net/package/util/shell/GoShell"} 
  Tool that allows you to open Shell in fullscreen on a separate screen.

@{b}Closing Remarks@{ub}

The recent uploads show that even in 2025, the Aminet archive is far from
static, new games, useful utilities, development tools, and creative
packs continue to appear, reminding us that the Amiga community remains
creative and active.

Dust off your A1200, fire up WinUAE or an RTG setup, there's fresh
material waiting. Keep an eye on Aminet, explore these packages, and
maybe build something new yourself.

See you in the next edition of Aminet Pulse.

@endnode

@node edwinoosterkampinterview -"Edwin van den Oosterkamp Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Edwin van den Oosterkamp@{ub}
============================================================================

@{b}1. First of all, could you tell us a little about yourself and how you first 
discovered the Amiga?@{ub}

My name is Edwin van den Oosterkamp and I was born in a small city in the 
Netherlands called Culemborg. I studied micro electronic design at the 
Hogeschool van Utrecht and have worked for pro-audio/broadcast equipment 
manufacturers most of my professional life. The first computer we had at 
home was a Commodore 64 and at the time most of my friends had one too. 
Later on we all had heard of the Amiga, with loads of colours and even 
stereo digitized sound (imagine that!). Then a close friend bought an 
Amiga 500 and when I saw it I knew I had to have one too. So I saved up 
all money from the Saturday job I did while studying and bought an Amiga 
500 a couple of months later. My friend and I had both been programming 
assembly on the C64 and of course switched over to doing the same on the 
Amiga. 

For me the Amiga is not only about nostalgia, it is also a system I simply 
like to use. I still own both Amigas I bought back in the day (a 500 and a 
1200) and I have always had a desk with an Amiga on it in my study. To be 
honest, in the period between 2000 and 2012 the Amiga may have only been 
powered on once a month or less, but it was on my desk and ready to be used. 

@{b}2. Many Amiga users have heard of the BassMX. For those unfamiliar, could 
you explain what the BassMX board is and what problem it solves?@{ub}

BassMX takes the audio from each of the Amiga's audio outputs, filters each 
so that only the low frequencies are kept and mixes that with the unfiltered 
audio from the other output. For example, it takes the audio from the left 
output, filters it so only the bass is kept and then mixes that with the 
unfiltered right output. It does the same with the audio of the right output 
in order to mix it with the left audio. This way the audio sounds more 
balanced when listening on speakers while at the same time retaining the 
stereo image of the audio. Since it only mixes the bass I decided to call 
it BassMX. 

@{b}3. What motivated you to design the BassMX? Was it something you personally 
needed, or did you see a wider gap in the community?@{ub}

One of my favourite things about the Amiga is the demo scene. Close the 
curtains, turn up the volume and enjoy the show. My Amiga has always been 
connected to my stereo for this reason, but hearing the beat coming from 
only one speaker always kinda bugged me. I could "fix" this with the "mono" 
switch on the amp, but losing the stereo image was too big a price to pay 
for having the beat on both speakers.

The basic idea for mixing only the bass came to me many years ago but I 
never really did anything with it. Until a couple of years ago when on a 
whim I simply tried it out within the Audacity audio editor. It allowed me 
to filter the audio and then flip the channels and mix it back into the 
original audio. I was surprised with how good the end result sounded. I then 
built a prototype on a bit of experimentation board, which kinda worked. 
Then I decided to just design a PCB and make a few of these in case anybody 
else was interested. I did not expect many people to be interested as for a 
lot of people the way the Amiga sounds is part of their nostalgia. But I was 
wrong as a lot of people have told me that they like the effect that BassMX 
gives.

@{b}4. What were some of the biggest technical challenges you faced in designing 
the BassMX, and how did you overcome them?@{ub}

It was not really a big challenge, but the one issue I had was with an old 
phone charger that turned out to be very noisy. It was a 5V charger that 
pre-dated USB chargers but happened to already have the correct barrel 
connector on it. When I tested the first version of the PCB it all worked 
fine until I tested it with this particular old phone charger. This charger 
caused a whining noise in the background. Only audible when the Amiga was 
quiet and the volume was turned up, but still unacceptable in my opinion. 
So I tried out different ways of filtering the power input and in the end 
settled on an active filter that completely removes any trace of the whining 
noise of that phone charger. This was important since I wanted users to be 
able to use any power supply to power the board. I then had to modify the 
design of the circuit board and have these new design boards manufactured 
as well.

@{b}5. You´ve documented parts of the design process on your blog. Do you see 
yourself as more of a hardware tinkerer, a software developer, or a bit of 
both?@{ub}

Both to be honest. And I have always been. For my first proper job I was 
hired to help write firmware for a digital portable recorder. As a hardware 
engineer who knows how to write software, my main task at the time was 
writing the code that interfaced with the hardware. Even recently during the 
recent chip shortage I found myself designing a new audio interface for one 
of our products (as the original chips were no longer available) and 
subsequently adapting the firmware to make it work like the original audio 
interface.

@{b}6. The Amiga scene has always thrived on community projects. How has the 
feedback from users influenced BassMX and your other work?@{ub}

Thinking back, I don't think I would've created BassMX as it is now without 
the nice feedback I've received for my Amiga books. I would probably have 
created the version on experimentation board for myself but not designed a 
PCB and then build a number of them for fellow Amigans to use. What also 
helped was that Dave (Velociraptor) from the "This Week In Retro" podcast 
was complaining about the Amiga stereo separation just when I had received 
the first batch of power-whine-fixed PCBs - this told me there could indeed 
be more people interested in this. When I announced it on a thread on EAB I 
also got a nice response there. I have alo received nice responses from 
musicians and DJs who use BassMX with the Amigas in their setup.

@{b}7. Apart from BassMX, you´ve written books and articles. Could you tell us 
about your writing - what subjects you´ve covered, and how your Amiga 
background influenced them?@{ub}

When I was a teenager I liked to write short stories but depicting 
conversations between characters in the story has always been my weak point. 
I did write a couple of AmigaGuide manuals for some software I released back 
in the day, but that was not really of influence on my professional writing. 
It was really by happenstance that I started writing professional 
documentation for our end users (as in, nobody else wanted to do it). And 
writing technical documentation for non-technical end-users has since then 
always been on my CV as part of my technical skills. The main subject was 
always "How to use the product" and these were not published as such, but 
were part of the product delivery. Of the three Amiga books I wrote the 
first is an introduction into programming the classic AmigaOS, the second 
is about bare-metal programming the hardware and the third is about writing 
Amiga software that uses the network.

@{b}8. Looking back, what role has the Amiga played in your personal and 
professional life?@{ub}

The Commodore 64 and the Amiga both have played a decisive role in my life. 
Programming the C64 taught me a lot about interrupts and programming the 
Amiga taught me a lot about multi-tasking, shared libraries and user 
interfaces. But the Amiga also allowed me to play with samplers, audio 
editors and sound trackers. I would never have started out writing low-level 
code to interface directly with hardware had it not been for the Amiga 
teaching me just that. The Amiga also taught me writing software on systems 
with limited resources like RAM and CPU power. Writing software for embedded 
systems has a lot of similarities with writing software for a stock Amiga in 
that respect.

@{b}9. The retro computing scene is very active today. How do you see the Amiga 
community compared to the early days?@{ub}

Back in the day I had a few friends with Amigas and through one of them I 
knew a bunch of guys running a monthly Amiga meet in a town not too far 
away. Getting hold of software was not easy as we did not have any computer 
stores in our little city. Neither did any of the towns nearby. News about 
Commodore or the Amiga I got by being subscribed to the Dutch Amiga 
Magazine, which was a great read, but only came once every two months. My 
hardware purchases were mostly done at one of two annual computer tradeshows 
in the Netherlands.

Nowadays thanks to the Internet I communicate with fellow Amigans across the 
globe. News about my favourite systems is only a few clicks away. Various 
websites sell Amiga hardware that I can purchase without having to leave the 
house. For me personally the community is therefore much more alive today 
than it was back in the day. The only thing I miss is the daily Amiga 
related chat with my fellow Amiga-owning students - as my work colleagues 
have no clue what I'm talking about.. 

@{b}10. Do you have any advice for today´s hobbyists who want to design their 
own hardware or software for classic systems like the Amiga?@{ub}

Go for it! And ignore negative people who will tell you there is no 
need/point. When my first Amiga programming book was published (in 2019) 
the initial response in a number of Amiga forums was "why?". If I had asked 
there beforehand I would have never started. The Amiga community is rather 
large and varied - there is a good chance that whatever good idea you have 
will be found similarly good by other people in the community. But don't 
set your goals too far ahead, make them reachable. It is better to start 
with something manageable and finish that, than to start something epic and 
lose heart halfway. It is supposed to be a hobby and for fun - don't make it
feel like work.

@{b}11. Finally, what´s next for you - any upcoming projects you can share with 
us?@{ub}

There are a couple of Amiga related subjects that I have in the back of my 
head as a possibility for a 4th book and there are a number of other 
hardware projects that I'm on and off playing with. But since this all 
happens in my spare time a lot of other things take precedence over what 
basically are my hobby projects. Sometimes I lose interest in a project 
(due to something more interesting coming up) and then pick it back up a 
few years later. For these reasons I never announce anything until it is 
ready, as I don't want to promise something and then don't deliver. And 
feeling to be forced to finish something makes it feel like meeting a work 
deadline - something I do not want to introduce into my private life!

@endnode

@node aidanholmesinterview "Aidan Holmes Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Aidan Holmes@{ub}
============================================================================

@{b}1. You've undertaken a wide range of Amiga-related projects in recent 
years, both hardware and software. Could you begin by sharing what first 
drew you to developing for the Amiga platform?@{ub}

The Amiga was my first platform with a C compiler using Dice. It felt like 
my first real programming on an OS although I'd previously used Basic on the 
ZX Spectrum, which never felt close to the real system. I'd only written 
some shell apps back in the Amiga in the early 90s and didn't get much 
further than that.

I came back to development on the Amiga after several hardware projects on 
the Raspberry Pi and Arduino. The Amiga is very much like an embedded 
environment and the OS is a great layer sitting on top of that hardware. The 
people around the Amiga also keep me coming back to the projects, with so 
many new ideas and great support from the user community.

@{b}2. One of your most notable recent works is the PCMCIACD.device driver. For 
readers unfamiliar with it, could you explain its purpose and what inspired 
you to create it?@{ub}

The driver supports the external PCMCIA CD-ROM drives created by Sony for 
their Vaio range of laptops. I had an IDE ATAPI CD-ROM drive already working 
on my A1200 and A600 using IDE buffer hardware. It had long ribbon cables 
coming out of the side of the case meaning I couldn't close the Amiga and it 
looked a real mess. That setup didn't make it easy to check out the latest 
CD-ROM from Amiga Future or CD games. At the time e-bay had the occasional 
Vaio CD-ROM selling at good prices and I wondered why we didn't have a 
driver for the Amiga.

@{b}3. What were the main technical challenges involved in enabling the Amiga 
to communicate with modern PCMCIA CD-ROM drives?@{ub}

I had to study a few driver implementations to really get a handle of the 
PCMCIA port and I'd say that the Aros project was a huge benefit for 
reference material. Technically the biggest challenge is the memory 
implementation mismatches between Intel and Motorola. Most PCMCIA hardware 
will be for Intel style PCs, which stopped me getting the full 16 bits of 
data until I picked up on the right code implementation. Following that it 
was just a job of building the ATA and ATAPI implementation required. This 
is well documented, but there were challenges with full SCSI command set vs 
ATAPI and this needed a few patches to provide all the emulation needed to 
support older games.

@{b}4. The Amiga's PCMCIA interface has certain limitations, such as the 
lack of DMA support. How did these constraints influence your development 
process and design choices?@{ub}

Without DMA the CPU has to handle each byte or word of memory and ensure it 
gets written to the device and back to main memory. This isn't really any 
worse than the IDE interface on the Amiga which is also missing DMA. My goal 
really wasn't to have the fastest CD-ROM access, but instead it was to 
improve the experience and have a plug and play driver where you could be 
accessing your compact flash card on moment and then browsing a CD-ROM the 
next. The Amiga PCMCIA can provide the required power without need external 
power supplies, which is a major feature of the Vaio drives, and I think 
this is why the device is so interesting for the Amiga. To answer the 
question properly; I didn't feel constrained with the limitations, and the 
driver could play back CDXL videos at close to 20 FPS.

@{b}5. How would you describe the current level of compatibility of your 
driver? Are there specific drive models or configurations that tend to 
perform best?@{ub}

The PCGA-CD51 is the primary drive, which I'd say is the best CD-ROM. It 
doesn't need external power and just works to plug-in and go. I have a 
CRX75A which is also a burner and probably capable of much higher speeds, 
but it needs external power an it's never the drive I dig out for a game 
or browse a CD. The driver works with the PCGA-DVD51 and also older 
PCGA-CD5 (if the lasers still work). Sony needed to keep backwards 
compatibility with their older laptops so it seems to be a solid range of 
drives that work with 16 bits.

I expect that this driver may work with other manufacturer devices, but 
getting hold of them is either too expensive to bother with or just not 
available.

@{b}6. What has the community response been like to the PCMCIACD driver and 
your other releases? Have you received any particularly useful feedback or 
collaboration offers?@{ub}

I've had a lot of great feedback from the community. Some people just 
saying thanks for supporting the hardware and other people providing useful 
feedback and issues. Everyone has been really patient and I've tried to 
implement as much as I can to make it work with all games. I'm involved with 
the Robin Hood Amiga Group in Nottingham, where I also get to meet up with 
some key folk within the Amiga dev community. Rob Smith has worked on the 
Dynaport driver for BlueSCSI and I built a UI to support the setup and 
diagnostics through some code rework of my PCMCIACD implementation.

@{b}7. Turning to your Amiga Laser Mouse project - what motivated you to 
modernize the original tank mouse design with a laser sensor?@{ub}

It's not my project, but instead one developed by gps79 and Eins. I've 
only picked up on the development of the driver and forked an 
implementation to fix some issues. One odd thing about this project has 
been the disconnect between hardware and software. Eins obviously wanted to 
share the hardware but had concerns about someone commercially creating an 
all-in-one version and profiting. In the end, the dev work was done and 
made available through gps79's firmware. I've tried to tie that together 
again into one place. I can understand Eins concern and could say that the 
PCMCIACD work has had the same outcome with people buying and selling the 
drives for additional profit, thus pushing up prices. Then again, I've made 
the Vaio drives worth something again so there was always going to be an 
impact. This shows how important the Amiga market still is in the vintage 
computer space.

@{b}8. That project required PCB design and firmware modification. Could you 
describe some of the technical considerations and difficulties you 
encountered during development?@{ub}

I can't really comment on the PCB design as it was Eins work. What I've 
found is that the Amiga tank mice have about 4 variations and getting the 
PCB to work in all needs some adjustment. I had to drill a hole in one 
corner because my mouse had a plastic support, whilst other people don't 
have this and their buttons are arranged differently instead.

The firmware was mostly built in gps79's firmware, but for some reason the 
quadrature phasing was incorrect. It was a very simple fix to swap two 
inputs around. I'm not sure if this has been caused by a PCB alteration 
making the firmware incorrect. I fixed it and made it available as a fork 
on my GitHub.

@{b}9. Your External Gotek Conversion project also caught attention. What 
problem were you aiming to solve with that build, and what were the key 
steps in making it work reliably?@{ub}

It was something I documented early on in my return to the Amiga. With so 
many ADFs available I wanted to use this but didn't need or want to remove 
my internal drives. As with anything I do, I document for myself so I don't 
forget what I did and also share with the community.

The Gotek conversation work took the existing drive emulator and built the 
drive into a shell of an old external floppy with 26 pin interface. The 
project shows the mapping of the Shugart 34 pin on the Gotek into required 
26 pin for Amiga external floppy devices. This provided a working example 
for anyone with failing external floppy drives who wanted to reuse as a Gotek.

@{b}10. You have also designed a replacement Amiga power supply using modern 
components. What do you see as the most important factors for ensuring 
safety and stability in PSU replacements for legacy hardware?@{ub}

This was a build from MsMadLemon from her YouTube. There's not a lot of new 
ideas here although I quite like the neon on/off switch :)

@{b}11. Your article on connecting the Amiga to the internet using a Raspberry
Pi demonstrates an interesting bridge between old and new technology. What 
were the main technical challenges in achieving that connection?@{ub}

The Pi is the Swiss Army of the computer world. Nearly everyone has one and 
many are in drawers (I know because I have them). Why not utilise for the 
internet? At the time this was what you would use for network access unless 
you had a PCMCIA network card or big box Amiga. I'd say that this is less 
important now with the Pilpbox, A314, PicoWyFy, Dynaport and PCMCIA cards 
which run much faster than the old Amiga serial port.

@{b}12. Looking across all these projects, what motivates you to continue 
developing new solutions for vintage systems like the Amiga?@{ub}

I wouldn't call myself nostalgic for the old days of the Amiga, but instead 
it's the Motorola 68k at the heart of the machine. I used this CPU in my 
University Labs whilst studying Computer Science and it was deemed the best 
example of a modern processor. I don't actually dev at low level, but I know 
that this is in reach and easy if needed. The practical reason is that I 
still own an A500 and A1200.

@{b}13. Finally, are there any upcoming developments, updates, or entirely new 
projects that you are currently exploring or hope to undertake in the near 
future?@{ub}

I have a few things on the go. The latest one is the Floppy Disk controller 
for the Sony FA-P1. This allows 1.44 Mb PC floppy disks on an Amiga with a 
PCMCIA port. It's pretty cool because you can have a 1.44 Mb Fast File 
System floppy on the Amiga as well as full 1.44 FAT disks you can 
interchange with a PC. It's really retro and probably unimportant with all 
the compact flash, networking and Goteks, but it was a real effort to get 
ready. Implementations are on Aminet and there are still fixes for this to 
get it working, but very much in-progress.

The other, long term build, is a Bluetooth stack for the Amiga. This started 
with PCMCIA Bluetooth card implementations and has got to a point where it 
can pair with a Phone or PC device and exchange files over ObEx. It's very 
basic at the moment and hit it's first milestone with more features to 
follow.

In the near future I expect to pick up some of the driver work ongoing with 
the SPIder hardware from Niklas (author of A314 and PicoWyFy). Niklas has 
a device already built to support SPI devices through the clock port header. 
There's not much more to say at this point, but the SPI hardware opens up 
further networking, MP3 decoding, LED illumination, sensor controls and 
loads of other more modern devices.

@endnode

@node zooperdaninterview "Dan -Zooperdan- Thoresen Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Dan "Zooperdan" Thoresen@{ub}
============================================================================

@{b}1. Dan, could you start by introducing yourself to readers who may not know
you yet? How did you first get involved with the Amiga, and what originally 
drew you to develop for it?@{ub}

My backstory is not terribly interesting. I'm an old geezer who got my
first home console in 1977 (Conic TVG-SD-01 Pong system). From that point
on computers and games have been a significant part of my life. A life that
changed when C64 arrived, and changed monumentally again with the release
of Amiga 500. Ever since I got my hands on an Amiga 500 in 1987 it's been
my favorite computer. I never even bothered with all the consoles and other
systems that came later. I started early to get into programming. I made my
first simple games using BASIC on a couple of different systems (C64,
SpectraVideo, MSX, Dragon32). Fast forward to recent years and I'm still
making simple games in BASIC, albeit Blitz Basic now. I have decades of
programming experience on PC using a variety of languages, but I find it
cathartic and enjoyable to challenge myself by working within the
restrictions of a retro platform. Blitz Basic offer me the right amount of
challenge while still letting me iterate and create with some efficiency. I
have 4 working Amigas (500 KS1.2, 500 KS1.3, 500+ and 1200) set up for
testing and occasional gaming (That reminds me; I need to get a 600).
People who know me well know that I run dungeoncrawlers.org and am a
hardcore dungeon crawler fan, perhaps even more so than Amiga. Some of my
best gaming experiences have been on Amiga with games like Bard's Tale, Eye
of the Beholder, Dungeon Master and Might & Magic III. I've hosted several
dungeon crawler game jams and also run a dedicated Discord server for fans
of the genre.

@{b}2. Many of your recent projects, like YEET, LUMA, and AmiKlotski, combine
classic Amiga charm with clever, modern puzzle design. What inspires your 
game concepts, and how do you decide which ideas are worth turning into full 
releases?@{ub}

Two of those you mentioned (YEET and AmiKlotski) were suggested to me as
ideas by AmigaLive :) AmiKlotski as a "reimagination" of a PD game called
DAD. Initially I planned to call my game MOM (lol) but ended up with a much
more boring name! Me and AmigaLive often spitball ideas and concepts which
is a great help as a solo developer. Sometimes the hardest part is the game
idea. LUMA is an adaptation of a C64 game by Simon Jameson (Shallan). For
ideas I also visit game sites like Kongregate and Itch.io to find small
golden nuggets which I believe could be a good fit for Amiga. That's how I
found the idea behind PJUSK. It was a small Flash game called HpAtkDef I
found on Kongregate.

@{b}3. Let's talk about YEET! Could you tell us how this project started, what 
the core idea behind the gameplay is, and what makes it unique among your 
previous works?@{ub}

YEET was born through a conversation I had with AmigaLive. We were
discussing various game ideas and he suggested I take a look at a game
called Fling! on iPhone. I liked the concept and started outlining the
project. At first the plan was to just make a single screen game with a
string of puzzles that you go through, but the scope creep monster called
and ordered a lot of fluff and stuff :) What makes it unique for me is
probably that it's the game I spent the most time creating and debugging,
even if it might not look it, YEET has the biggest scope in any game I
made. YEET has been very well received in the community so the three whole
days of fighting mem leaks was well worth it :) The core gameplay is
simple; Push runes of the board until one rune remains. You can only push
runes in a straight line and only if there is at least one tile space
between them. Despite simple mechanics many levels are quite challenging.

@{b}4. From a technical perspective, YEET runs on very modest hardware, just an
Amiga 500 with 512 KB. Was it challenging to make the game fit within those 
limits, and do you enjoy working within those classic constraints?@{ub}

It was a little bit challenging in terms of memory management, mostly
because we didn't want to aggressively reduce the sample quality in the
music. Initially YEET ran on a 500 without 512KB extra, but chiptune style
music were not a great match for the game. As mentioned earlier I had to
find and fix a lot of mem leaks and that was probably the most challenging
part of making the game. At one point I almost gave up the project.

@{b}5. You've mentioned in past Amiga News articles that you use BlitzBasic and
other retro-focused tools. Can you describe your development setup today,
hardware, emulators, workflow, and how you test your games?@{ub}

For the most part I develop using AmiBlitz3 on WinUAE with a souped up
configuration (*040 Super-Hires JIT + tons of memory) but I also sometimes
use my 1200 *030 (128mb ram) for development. As mentioned I have a couple
Amigas that I use to test my games. I think it is important when you are a
developer to test on the actual system(s) you're targeting. My workflow
differs a lot but common denominators are Aseprite for pixel art, Tiled for
level/map creation, Goldwave for audio editing and a bunch of small
homebrew command line tools for various batch operations like png-to-iff
conversion, wav-to-8svx conversion etc. I often use AI as part of my tool
chain but never directly. I use generative AI output as a resource for
further refining or photo-bashing. I use ChatGPT sometimes to help with
mundane tasks like .json/data manipulation, translations, story writing
etc. As a solo developer with limited authoring and graphical ability, and
fairly limited years left lol, I value the help I can get and anything that
can speed up my process is very welcome.

@{b}6. Your games often have smooth design, tight controls, and consistent
presentation. Do you handle all graphics, coding, and music yourself, or do 
you collaborate with other creators for certain aspects?@{ub}

I do all graphics and coding myself, but as mentioned I do get some
starter help here and there by generative AI. I rarely ever make my own
music. I have made some tunes over the years but it takes more out of me
than both the coding and graphics combined. I'm fortunate to know a
demoscene musician who made great music for several of my games. I actually
prefer to work solo. It's hard enough to make games and I don't need the
added pressure of running a project and managing other people.

@{b}7. What part of Amiga development do you find the most rewarding? And what 
part still drives you mad even after all these years?@{ub}

The most rewarding part is definitely working within the limitations. As
a PC developer speed or file optimizations is not even a thing you think
about. Coincidentally; working within the limitations is also what drives
me mad lol. Also, the influx of different hardware upgrades introduces
potential issues we didn't have before. Back in the early 90's when someone
made a game for an Amiga then you knew it would run. That's not always true
today.

@{b}8. The Amiga community seems to be thriving again with new games, jams, and
releases. How do you see the current state of the Amiga scene, and what role 
do you think events like your Amiga Tool Jam play in keeping it alive?@{ub}

The Amiga community is definitely thriving and probably stronger than it
has ever been, mostly because of the way we communicate and share our
passion now with streams, videos, webpages, discords and social media in
general. The fact that one can hop on Twitch any given day and find an
Amiga stream, or that there seems to be at least one game released for
Amiga every week is mindblowing. I firmly believe that jams are an
important component of any community. Whether it's a jam about literary
works, music composition, game or tool development they bring members of
the community together and it invites people to learn and challenge
themselves. As mentioned, I've hosted several dungeon crawler jams which
combined have resulted in hundreds of new games for people to play and
raising awareness to thousands of people. On a personal level attending in
time-restricted game jams is a great motivator and excellent way to learn
time management, planning and how to "complete" a project. I wrote
"complete" because a jam entry are rarely ever fully completed in the sense
of a commercial release-worthy product. It's "completed" because you did
what you set out to; you devised a concept and scope, executed it and
submitted. That feeling is special, and the feedback and interactions with
the community is priceless.

@{b}9. Looking back, how has your approach to game development changed from
your earliest projects to now? Were there any key lessons or "aha" moments 
that shaped how you build games today?@{ub}

If you mean my earliest projects on Dragon32 or C64 in 1982 then a lot
has changed, lol. In more recent years when I picked up developing using
Blitz Basic on Amiga again, there has been a learning curve and an exercise
in trying to remember how I did this and that. The biggest change or Aha!
is definitely the introduction of AI, or more specifically ChatGPT. It
allows me to focus on the game creation part while leaving the boring and
repetitive tasks to AI. I have likely made hundreds of different level
editors, combat calculators, file manipulators, data conversion tools etc.
from scratch over the years, and I'm at a point in my life where I don't
want or need to do those things anymore. That's the biggest help for me now.

@{b}10. If someone today wanted to start developing for the Amiga, perhaps a
younger coder discovering it for the first time, what advice would you give
them?@{ub}

It depends on how much programming experience the person have. Scorpion
Engine is a great place to start getting your feet wet with game creation
on Amiga. It ease you into familiarization about game loops and logic,
sprites, bobs, palette management and even some more complex concepts.
Beyond that I would definitely recommend Blitz Basic and AmiBlitz3. We have
a dedicated Blitz Basic Discord server with a strong, helpful and growing
community. There are a lot of code examples and resources available to get
you going.

@{b}11. Beyond YEET, can you share any hints about what you're working on next?
Is there another puzzle game, or perhaps something entirely different on the 
horizon?@{ub}

I just released a small word search game. It was something I wanted to
do for a while now, because I love these games myself. I am not sure what's
next for me now. I have a couple ideas I'm juggling. In the future I plan
to make a dungeon crawler game but I am not ready for that yet. I still
need a couple more learning projects before I go down that rabbit hole. One
of the ideas I'm entertaining is a deck-builder game with top-down open
world map movement where combat and events are resolved via a card game.
AmigaLive also has some ideas, so let's see what happens :D

@{b}12. Finally, how can fans best follow your work and support your projects?@{ub}

My website is zoopersoft.com which is the home of my "software company"
and has links to most of my stuff. There you'll also find the link to our
Blitz Basic Discord.

@endnode

@node electricblacksheepinterview "Electric Black Sheep Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Electric Black Sheep@{ub}
============================================================================

@{b}1. First, could you introduce yourself and tell us how Electric Black Sheep 
started, is it a solo project or a small team effort?@{ub}

There are two members. Me (László) and my twin brother (Imre). We are not 
a "group" in a classic meaning. We brainstorming ideas in family meetings. 
Our mindset is very similar so making the games for the Amiga is more like 
fun and recreational. Both of us has our own creative side. Imre is the AMOS 
coder. He likes to experimenting with different techniques like processing 
and compressing iff animations, vector graphics or put some interesting 
effect into our games. He made a hell lot of pixel gfx too, the background 
tiles in "Project:Quest" is 100% his creation.  I make gfx too but i'm 
working mostly on the animations (characters, fmv,..), making them pixel by 
pixel or 3d modelling/rendering. 

2. What first captured your interest in the Amiga platform, and when did 
you decide you'd try making new games on it in the modern era?

We have been typing on the keyboard since we were 8 years old, but we only 
switched to Amiga during high school. We didn't know the platform; all we 
knew was that it had good value for money and good capabilities relative to 
that price. As youngsters, we were primarily interested in games, but the 
fact that it could be used for anything else became clear as we went along. 

In hindsight, it was a fortunate choice, as we could both use it for 
graphics due to our visual orientation, so we liked it. Compared to other 
machines of the era, the amiga didn't have limits. We previously practiced 
basic programming on C16, but at this time the knowledge of the software 
needed for programming were missing. There was no internet, and the 
magazines were almost exclusively about games, so there was nothing to pique 
our imagination. (We weren't excited about it; we didn't feel the urge). 

The urge came later, when we dusted it off for nostalgia, but a few things 
were missing, which are easier and cheaper to implement with today's 
mindset. These included, for example, the Arduino mouse emulator, RAM 
expansion, and a DIY HDD controller, and I think the "bug" (interest) came 
with this, along with the ability to get any software online. László deals 
with programming at a professional level, so he thought he would try to see 
what could be squeezed out of such a machine. For the sake of simplicity, 
he chose AMOS, which is closer to modern development environments, and 
created the first version of Star Dust Wars. Its simplicity is how it 
infected me as well. One project followed another.

@{b}3. In your view, what advantages or charms does the Amiga still offer for 
developers and players today?@{ub}

For those who grew up in the 80s, this doesn't need to be explained. It does 
have its limitations, but these machines are not overly complicated. Perhaps 
the limitations were precisely what made the creators consider what and how 
they incorporated into their software, instead of just dumping in 
unnecessary things, claiming that this would make a program "more" and that 
today's machines can handle it anyway... even an infinite loop will run on 
them. So, less is sometimes more, and among retro lovers, it's a platform 
that, while perhaps not usable in everyday life anymore, is not too far from 
modern user interfaces in terms of usability/learnability, yet it's not just 
a blinking cursor.

@{b}4. What is your typical toolchain or workflow when making Amiga games 
(e.g. language, assembler, emulator, testing on real hardware)?@{ub}

Sometimes we just draw, and if it turns out well, it can be the basis for a 
game. In parallel, we also create codes that are not games, just out of 
curiosity. The point of this would be to see how a given thing could be 
done, or if it can be done at all/if we can or want do it later, and how it 
looks/behaves in different environments? Since AMOS is a Basic language that 
also uses fairly specific commands, you can progress with it relatively 
easily and quickly. We primarily work with an emulator, which makes 
preparations and testing easier, but the final tests are also performed on 
real hardware (on A500-A600-A1200 stock or fully expanded with RAM and HDD 
but without accelerator... and we also have a Vampire). So, game programs 
are sometimes created on a sudden impulse when the test codes meet each 
other in the appropriate environment. The main thing is that they should be 
varied, so they possibly provide a challenge and joy not only to the players 
but also to the creators. We start to refine them, build in what is 
necessary, and delete what is superfluous... optimization is one of our 
obsessions, that only that code runs, and only when it is needed. (Respect 
to the retro enthusiasts because the speed of today's machines, some people 
no longer even think about this). By sending the tests and ideas to each 
other, we reach the point where we call something final. We test among 
ourselves; we don't send it out to external people, as we are often not even 
sure of the direction, let alone the final result.

@{b}5. Turning to Star Dust Wars: Director's Cut - how did that project begin, 
and what was your vision for it?@{ub}

I think the project started when We saw in several places that people were 
trying to play video films on Amiga. They tried to get the maximum out of it 
(See: AGABlaster). This was spectacular, but also disturbing. These formats 
are uncompressed, so their size is very large, requiring extremely fast HDD, 
not to mention that a stronger CPU is also associated with it. Those who 
have enough RAM could help themselves by copying it to RAM and playing the 
video from there... but who has hundreds of MB for a 5-minute video clip, 
and why not compress the format!? This is where the process started, from 
which we first created an audio player used in our games that streams the 
data from the storage and occupies only 22kb of RAM. Only the image/video 
part was missing, which involved greater complications, and admittedly, it 
could be better, but it's ours... and it was finally completed, under the 
name AnimPlayer; this player program is the basis of SDWC. The idea seemed 
natural that this AnimPlayer could even run in the background of a game if 
things were synchronized, as we had experimented with something similar 
before, based on the blitter lines used in our Bad Apple demo (vectorized). 

There wasn't really a vision; the whole point of the test was just whether 
we could solve this under AMOS or not, but even if we could, the 
possibilities are quite limited, since it is a pre-recorded animation that 
cannot adapt so well (only to pre-stored changes).

@{b}6. What were the most challenging aspects to making Star Dust Wars, did you
create any custom routines/tricks?@{ub}

Technically... AMOS fundamentally handles animation and sound, but in the 
default case, it does so by fully loading them into ChipRAM. If it doesn't 
fit because we want something bigger, we had to create a workaround for this 
case. We didn't have much trouble with the sound because we only had to 
handle loading and streaming. The animation was a bit tougher nut to crack. 

There are several reasons for this (*I'll explain this in a moment). 

Normally, a drawn animation means an object moves on a static background. 
The IFF anim format we use also supports this by storing only the movement 
from successive frames, thereby reducing unnecessary data volume. We also 
had trouble here because the backgrounds we created moved in full-screen 
size, and if even one pixel changed, the format treated it as (area) change, 
unnecessarily increasing the data volume to the point where it almost no 
longer made sense to store it as IFF anim. Thus, one goal was to reduce this 
data volume, not only because it was necessary, but also because the reduced 
data volume would allow animations to be "streamed" not only from light-
speed HDD. Through a long process of experimentation, we also created a 
program that can significantly filter out unnecessary changes (dithering, 
noise, ...) from successive frames in a specific (but adjustablle) way, 
without destroying the visual experience and also taking the data format 
into account. I haven't seen an example of this type of program.

The part of the program that reduces HAM animations deserves special 
mention, because in that case, due to the nature of the display method, 
changes made to the image may generate additional errors not only in the 
current image but also in subsequent ones.

In our opinion, the result was quite successful, considering the content 
and dynamism of the animations. This pride applies to the finished 
animations, the preparation program, and the player, which could even run 
with 512 RAM... if it can process lthe loaded data quickly. *: Besides 
everything, it's also good to know that the animation command of AMOS 
contains a bug, which acted as an extra incentive for us. The essence of 
the bug is that the address of the last bitplane of a new animation frame 
within that frame cannot point to an address (offset) above 32kb. For those 
who don't know: a 320x256 image occupies 10 kb per bitplane, so problems 
can arise in the anim even in the case of a 16-color (4 bitplane, 4x10=40kb) 
frame. But... fortunately, we managed to fix this bug without external help, 
even though our knowledge of ASM is very... very low. Thus, one project 
actually depended on the other in a positive sense, even on the base (AMOS), 
but all's well that ends well, because the programs and the fix also had 
benefits. The models and animations used in the game were made by László... 
maybe he could have done them on the Amiga with LightWave, but these were 
made on PC... sorry, but we didn't want to wait decades for the render. 
Postscript: If anyone didn't notice, he even managed to implement 3d Hit 
Boxes on the Trenchrun level. (This means that the ships and projectiles 
get stuck on that.)

@{b}7. Thank you for that, aside from Star Dust Wars, you have made many other
well received games. Revenge of the Grinch (2024), was a wonderful game for
the Xmas season, similar to your Dungeon of Evil.

What motivated you to make a festive spin-off like Revenge of the Grinch, 
did it share any code/mechanics with Dungeon of Evil? Were there any 
obstacles during development?@{ub}

We create all our games in such a way that the graphics can be exchanged 
very easily. Not only does AMOS handle this by default, but we also do not 
put any protection on it that would make unauthorized interference 
difficult. This is not just for our own sake; it is also an opportunity for 
people who feel compelled to do so (Modders?). As we mentioned earlier, we 
often create drawings without knowing what they will be good for, and we 
just happened to have a similar themed scribble collection that we just had 
to complete. This results in a win-win situation; it's good for us because 
it's different, and maybe someone likes this one specifically and not the 
original. The atmosphere and intention are always there at Christmas, of 
course, but essentially, a large part of our figures were drawn earlier, so 
they don't get lost forever on our HDD (this can also be a motivation). The 
code, the engine, and the game mechanics are actually 99% the same, just 
fine-tuned for the theme. It also goes with this that the game can mean 
different things to everyone, and the feeling of Christmas can be different. 
We tried not to exaggerate the horror and humor elements in the game 
(e.g., Kevin's skeleton from Home Alone), because not everyone can or wants 
to handle them as they should, ...or as we would like. In our opinion, 
"it's just a game", but we often receive comments that object to certain 
elements, even if it is not the game itself but the most insignificant 
element of the program: an AI-generated loading screen. 

@{b}8. It can be a difficult balance to achieve in today's world, thank for the
game I greatly enjoyed it last year. Another seasonal game you made was 
Pumpkin (2024) a Halloween edition of a Pac-man style game, can you tell us
a bit about the game?@{ub}

Pumpkin was a very good lesson for us. We try not to manufacture our games 
all in the same mould. Observing the appearance of retro games, (I don't 
even know how many) ports of the original Pac-Man game was being published. 
It's an evergreen game, and not looking down on it, but to us, they looked 
the same, with no apparent differences. Thus, none of them offered anything 
new visually. The original game does not contain many graphical elements, 
it would not be difficult to replacicate them in a new form, so we only had 
to create the controller program. Here, we faced the fact of what a 
seemingly simple concept actually conceals. Creating a maze doesn't take 
long. We are fast and efficient in creating Tome maps, but the movement 
methods for enemies we have used so far did not work here, and any 
modifications we would have made to them would not have reproduced the 
ghosts' original behavior pattern. So, we didn't look into how much the 
map design and the movement (personality!) of the ghosts are built upon each 
other, and how unique this is. Incomprehension then turned into interest 
and challenge. Considering all the information, we finally did what we 
could. The ghosts were programmed based on description and observation, we 
don't say they move exactly as they should, but considering all the 
available information, it is a pretty good "approximation" of the original. 

The truth is that Pumpkin would not have been created if we had known what 
was under the skin. We always learn something new... now We even know the 
ghosts by their names. The game originally required 1 MB of chip RAM. Due 
to its simplicity, many may think it was due to negligence. No. In the case 
of AMOS, this level can be easily reached, because automatic graphical 
operations that we unfortunately cannot get rid of also run in the 
background. In the old days, almost all games ran with 512+512 RAM. We 
would support this if possible, but in the present case, we could only 
solve this with compromises, which means a small loss in terms of sounds. 
We completely agree with such requests and comply with them as long as it 
can be carried out without compromising the gaming experience. 

@{b}9. For both Revenge of the Grinch and Pumpkin, how do you balance nostalgia 
(faithfulness to classic styles) vs modern polish (smoothness, effects, 
extra features)?@{ub}

The basis of every game is the mechanics. If this gives the meaning, there 
is no point in changing it, and it shouldn't be changed. The appearance is 
another matter. Old games look the way they do not only because they were 
designed/drawn that way, but also because they had display limitations, 
and often couldn't have looked any other way. At least we have a choice. 
Due to the Amiga's features, it is sometimes not a challenge to make 
something prettier, but it is sometimes harder to make it as ugly as the 
original, but why do that if it's ugly? It is difficult to get the crazy 
movement of Tower of Evil running on C16 out of our minds. It was good as 
it was, but this was mainly due to the capabilities of the C16, but it did 
not really affect the gaming experience. For this reason, the same thing is 
prettier (and more natural) on Amiga, taking the original mechanics as a 
basis but implementing it with smooth movement (in the case of Xzap, this 
is a mission impossible). The snowfall is just the icing on a cake. If that 
were the goal, and the change does not convey the original feeling, then 
let's do something else or not call it that (if it can even be called that 
due to copyright protection).

@{b}10. What kind of feedback have you received from the Amiga community on 
Revenge of the Grinch and Pumpkin? Any bug reports or suggestions that 
surprised you?@{ub}

There are both negative and positive feedback. I (we?) consider it positive 
when we are praised (we carelessly don't react to this; we pocket it and 
move on), and there are also those who provide feedback that can positively 
influence the game and our future work. These include constructive 
criticism, opinions, suggestions, and missing details. We take all such 
requests into account if they are a good idea and do not deviate the project 
too much from the original direction, as that is the essence. There are also 
negative signals that we partially or not always agree with, as we approach 
things differently, so we cannot and do not want to deal with them. Some 
people like it, some don't, ...Ok but we won't be a battlefield.

@{b}11. In retrospect, is there anything in Revenge of the Grinch or Pumpkin 
that you wish you had designed differently, if time and memory weren't 
constraints?@{ub}

No :)

@{b}12. Looking ahead, are there more themed/seasonal games you'd like to build 
(for Christmas, Halloween, etc.)?@{ub}

Currently, there are none. (but the details are included above!)

