@node alineainterview "Alinea (www.amiga-shop.net) Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview: Alinea (www.amiga-shop.net)@{ub}
============================================================================

@{b}1. Could you briefly tell us how Amiga Shop was founded and how you came to 
specialise in Amiga hardware and accessories?@{ub}

The Amiga Shop was actually just a by-product, because Ricco and I actually 
only wanted to found an Amiga software company for the AmigaOS 4. We were 
both studying at the time and then founded the company in 2005. But when 
KDH-Datentechnik, our favourite dealer, closed its doors, we thought we had 
to close this gap and set up an online shop. We only had a few products at 
the beginning and added more and more over time. It didn't really take off 
until 2010, when Ricco left the company and Torsten joined, because he 
wanted to focus more on Amiga hardware.

@{b}2. What does a typical "day in the life" of your business look like?@{ub}

I think it's like in many companies. Early in the morning, all the emails 
are answered and then the orders are processed straight away. On normal 
days, you're done with the orders by lunchtime, but on Mondays, when a lot 
of orders have piled up over the weekend, it can happen that you spend the 
whole day working on orders.

Otherwise, in the afternoon there's production, testing and, of course, 
meetings with Torsten or our developer. Of course, there are also 
administrative tasks such as reordering goods or parts, or tax matters so 
that the tax office doesn't complain.

@{b}3. How has the Amiga-market changed over the last few years (hardware
availability, customer base, global shipping, etc.)?@{ub}

Yes, it has changed, and for the better. When I talk about the market, I am 
mainly referring to the classic Amiga market. The Amiga OS 4.1 market is 
unfortunately still very small and has been rather inactive. But the classic 
Amiga is on the upswing. A lot of hardware is currently needed and the 
demand for software is also increasing. All in all, demand is increasing, 
which of course benefits us greatly.

We ship worldwide, of course. And we would also say that the market is 
growing worldwide. Germany and the EU are very strong. USA, Australia, UK 
too, but the USA is currently a bit of a problem because of the customs 
policy.

@{b}4. What do you see as the biggest challenges and joys in keeping Amiga
systems alive and relevant today?@{ub}

There are various challenges you have with the Amiga. One is certainly that 
the Amiga is getting on in years and there is a need to change the 
capacitors to keep the system working properly. Many people don't realise 
this and troubleshooting is sometimes quite difficult.

But the Amiga users are very loyal and grateful and that is why we are 
always very pleased with our work.

@{b}5. From your perspective, which items are your biggest sellers (hardware, 
upgrades, accessories, software, etc.)?@{ub}

One of the best-selling products is certainly AmigaOS 3.2, but hardware such 
as the ArcadR joysticks or the Gotek drives are also doing very well. Of our 
products, the TV ports, Omniports, the Wodem and the repair kits are doing 
very well.

@{b}6. Have there been any items that surprised you by selling far better than 
expected (or conversely items you expected to sell well but didn't)?@{ub}

Yes, of course, there were items that sold worse than expected and some that 
sold unexpectedly well. The Amiga Beachball is one of the poorly performing 
products. It went very badly for years and at some point I added a ball to 
every order free of charge. Unfortunately, that was a mistake, because after 
a few years the demand for the ball was suddenly there and we didn't have 
any more.

A positive example, however, is the 4-fold Kickrom Flash adapter. We didn't 
think that the demand for such a product would be so high. The Kickrom Flash 
were and are constantly sold out ;)

@{b}7. Do you see any emerging trends (for example: new cases, modern upgrades, 
community-produced items, etc.)?@{ub}

Yes the trend is towards modern coloured cases with LED lighting and 
upgraded hardware like the PiStorm. I think the trend will continue and 
ventilation and tuning systems will be added.

@{b}8. Your website lists many items - do you manufacture some of the hardware
accessories yourselves or work under licence for Amiga-branded or Amiga-
compatible items?@{ub}

Most of our items are third party items that have to be purchased 
externally. In the meantime, however, we also have our own production and 
several developers on hand. We have an in-house developer and various 
external developers from whom we licence the hardware. Production then runs 
entirely through us. Alinea couldn't survive without the product, as the 
margins are naturally much better there than with external products. The 
shop now has over 800 items for the Amiga in its programme.

@{b}9. How do you decide which new products to bring in (or produce) for the 
Amiga community?@{ub}

That was very simple. We developed and produced what we wanted ourselves 
and was not available. We are passionate Amiga users and burn for the Amiga 
every second.

@{b}10. How do you engage with the Amiga community (forums, user groups, retro-
events, etc.) and how important is that community to your business?@{ub}

We are active in the most important forums in Germany, such as a1k.org
forum. We are also active in international forums, but rather sporadically. 
As far as Amiga events are concerned, we are very active and attend almost 
every Amiga event in Germany. The Amiga community there is really very 
active and many clubs and user groups organise meetings and fairs there. 
One of the most important fairs is of course the international Amiga fair 
in Mönchengladbach, the Amiga 40 Germany, which was just recently.

@{b}11. Where do you see the Amiga hobby/market going in the next 3-5 years
(hardware side, restoration side, software side)?@{ub}

I think the market will continue to grow and the number of users will 
increase. One problem is certainly the limited availability of hardware, 
which is reflected in the high prices of the A1200, for example. It is 
currently the most popular Amiga. The prices of the device are currently 
skyrocketing and many people can't afford an Amiga or simply can't get one. 

I hope that we will soon see new boards that can close this gap again. 
TheA1200 or other hardware solutions could contribute to this.

@{b}12. Is there anything you'd like the wider Amiga community (or newcomers) 
to know about your business or the work you do?@{ub}

I would just like to say that the Amiga community is a very great community. 
It's nice to see how much the users love their Amiga and put their heart 
and soul and work into it. We hope that the Amiga will continue for a long 
time to come and that the spirit and innovation it contains will be 
preserved forever.

Stay loyal to the Amiga, because it's worth it!

@endnode
